VALUES
	(142,NULL,NULL,2,'Dovecot Inn: Fire destroys 80% of historic pub','dovecot_inn_fire_destroys_80_of_historic_pub','Avon Fire & Rescue said they were â€œsatisfied that the fire at the Dovecote Inn started accidentally in the roof spaceâ€','A fire has caused severe damage to the historic Dovecote pub near Ashton Court, parts of which date back to the 1650s. Fire crews were called in the early hours of Thursday by the landlord of the pub who was alerted by an alarm, and discovered the site well ablaze. More than 50 firefighters from nine fire engines, including two aerial appliances and support vehicles, were involved trying to tame the fire. By 6am the fire had been put out but about 80% of the two-storey building had been destroyed. Avon Fire &amp; Rescue said they were &ldquo;satisfied that the fire at the Dovecote Inn started accidentally in the roof space&rdquo;. Fire crews left at about 2.30pm adding the structure of the building &ldquo;remains unsafe&rdquo;.','','BS4 3EN','51.43913779244131','-2.635146175634759',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 03:32:05',0),
	(143,NULL,NULL,2,'Trainee cider-makers sought for Somerset Orcharding Apprenticeship','trainee_cidermakers_sought_for_somerset_orcharding_apprenticeship','Shepton Mallet Cider Mill, nr Bristol, has teamed up with Yeovil College to train the next generation of cider-makers','A&nbsp;leading South West cider producer is launching a specialist Orcharding Apprenticeship scheme to get local youngsters learning the skills of growing cider apples.\r\nShepton Mallet Cider Mill, together with Yeovil College and local growers in Somerset, have developed the scheme to encourage more young people to opt for a career in an agricultural sector with the South West its heartland.\r\nGlobally, sales of high quality British cider have never been stronger, as consumers chose it as their drink of choice not only in the UK and Europe but around the world. Somerset has long been synonymous with cider production and the industry is keen to preserve this position by training a new generation of cider makers with specialised orcharding skills, creating a workforce to sustain the future of the cider industry.\r\nThe new Orcharding Apprenticeship programme starts this September and the Cider Mill is already interviewing for the first intake of new recruits eager to learn about Orchard Management.&nbsp;The programme will combine academic study with practical experience, including working alongside growers to learn how to plant apple trees, harvesting techniques and how to manage an orchard.\r\nBob Chaplin, Master Cider Maker at Shepton Mallet Cider Mill says: &ldquo;We identified we need good, young workers available to meet the increasing demand from cider makers and growers for trained, knowledgeable and skilled staff to work in cider orchards. It&rsquo;s vital that we preserve the skills that generations of cider makers have perfected and passed on. The scheme has been created to ensure we have a plan in place which does just that.&rdquo;\r\nHe added: &ldquo;The programme will also create valuable employment and training opportunities for students across Somerset and the South West.&rdquo;\r\nThe industry is led by well-known names, such as the Shepton Mallet Cider Mill with its portfolio of iconic South West cider brands, including: Blackthorn, Olde English, Addlestones and Natch.\r\nFor more information or to find out how to apply, please contact Yeovil College on 01935 845392 or email training@yeovil.ac.uk','','BS4 3EN','51.47470288782127','-2.6199541437744074',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 02:59:08',0),
	(144,NULL,NULL,2,'Designer vaginas in the media can encourage genital surgery','designer_vaginas_in_the_media_can_encourage_genital_surgery','The latest cutting-edge research will be unveiled at the Appearance Matters 6 conference, taking place in Bristol on 1-2 July 2014','Images of &lsquo;designer vaginas&rsquo; in the media can encourage consideration of genital surgery, according to the findings of a new report to be presented in Bristol this week. The shocking findings, the result of a labiaplasty study by Gemma Sharp and Prof. Marika Tiggemann from Flinders University in Australia, will be presented at 6th Appearance Matters conference, taking place&nbsp;at the&nbsp;Wills Memorial Building in Bristol on Tuesday and Wednesday (July 1-2, 2014). More and more women are undergoing cosmetic genital surgery and the most popular of these procedures is labiaplasty, also known as &lsquo;designer vagina&rsquo; surgery. This procedure involves the reduction of the vaginal lips, known as the labia, so the labia do not protrude. Women who have had greater exposure to images of vaginas in the media are more likely to consider labiaplasty according to new research being presented at the Appearance Matters conference in Bristol on Wednesday. The report indicates that close to 1 in 5 of the 351 women surveyed, aged between 18 and 69 years, had some interest in undergoing a labiaplasty procedure. The study also found that women who had greater exposure to images of female genitals through a range of media sources (television, Internet, advertising, and pornography) were more likely to be dissatisfied with their own genital appearance and consider labiaplasty. Furthermore, the study found that a significant percentage of women had received negative comments from romantic partners about the appearance of their genitals and a similarly sizeable number of women had discussed genital appearance with their friends, and both of these were related to a desire to undergo labiaplasty. Gemma Sharp explains, &ldquo;Our study is the first to systematically examine the role of the media, romantic partners and friends on women&rsquo;s consideration of labiaplasty. Our findings suggest a worrying trend of women becoming dissatisfied with the appearance of their genitals. We think that if women and their partners were made aware of the large variation in normal genital appearance this might help to alleviate some of their concerns about their own genitals.&rdquo; In addition to findings from the labiaplasty study, the Appearance Matters 6 conference will feature cutting edge research on visible difference, body image, cosmetic surgery, ethics, education, the media, weight and provision of care. More info&nbsp;here.','','BS4 3EN','51.43705115965591','-2.5394449579833918',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00',0),
	(145,NULL,NULL,2,'What\'s on in Bristol this weekend - July 4-6, 2014','whats_on_in_bristol_this_weekend_july_46_2014','Your guide to whatâ€™s on in Bristol this weekendâ€¦','<p>HOT PICK: Bristol Cycle Festival / Make Sunday Special @ City Centre (Sun) Make Sunday Special has linked up with Bristol Cycle Festival this Sunday for events in Corn Street, Small Street, St Nicholas Market and Castle Park. Highlights include Carnivelo &ndash; an opportunity to dress up, create a bike float or join in the carnival as you are &ndash; starting at 2pm in Castle Square. This year it&rsquo;s joined by Strictly Cycling, a bike dance performance by Bicycle Ballet who will also be running a workshop for visually impaired people at 1am in Castle square. More stall holders and food outlets will be open in St Nicholas Market and First Bus will continue with their discounted &pound;5 family ticket for travel on the Make Sunday Special days. Other events in the city to enjoy this weekend include the Wimbledon Men&rsquo;s final being screened in Millennium Square, the Henbury Steam Locomotive running trips along the Bristol Harbour Railway and the Bristol Comedy Garden in Queen&rsquo;s Square. MUSIC: Svalbard + Pariso @ The Gryphon (Sat) Pariso and Svalbard first met and played together on Sunday 17 March 2013 supporting Direwolves in &lsquo;the capital of champions&rsquo;, AKA Cardiff. To say their squalid love affair blossomed furiously quickly would be somewhat of an understatement. UK and European shows have since been embarked upon, vans split, many OTT meals shared. And now, this&hellip;see them live at this intimate hometown gig (for Svalbard). ARTS: Gimme Shelter Vintage Boutique @ The Lanes&nbsp;(Sun) An afternoon of shopping to include all the things we love about vintage fairs!&nbsp;Variety, individuality, one-offs, creativity, value, good food and great music. And bowling. The fair is free entry and is for anyone who has an interest in fashion, vintage clothes, records, jewellery, memorabilia, handmade, unique and one-off pieces. As well as quality vintage items there will also be local designers and creative exhibitors, who use vintage and recycled ethics we are also pleased to say that there will also be a number of Etsy shops joining us. Pop-up cafe courtesy of &lsquo;Mels Kitchen&rsquo; plus live music in the garden. All makes for a great afternoon, we think! THEATRE: Bunbury is Dead @ The Alma Tavern (Fri &amp; Sat) Composed almost entirely from Wilde&rsquo;s major works and masterfully arranged to form all-new dialogue, Bunbury is Dead follows the escapades of Bunbury, Algernon&rsquo;s fictitious invalid from The Importance of Being Earnest.&nbsp;This post-modern tribute is a sparkling, hilarious piece of twisted logic and high farce sprinkled with the inimitable wit of Oscar Wilde. More info&nbsp;here. FESTIVAL: Nibley Festival @ Nibley, Glos (Sat) Nibley is the friendly festival in a stunning Cotswold location. The best music, free entertainment for the kids, stalls, local beer, food from around the world &ndash; it&rsquo;s the recipe for a perfect day. Camp on Friday and Saturday to make a weekend of it. Run entirely by volunteers on a not-for-profit basis, Nibley is a rare festival gem. We may be small, but our attention to quality in everything we do makes us something very special. Acts include The Heavy, Turin Brakes, Skinny Lister and more. COMEDY: Al Murray and more&nbsp;@ Magners Bristol Comedy Garden (Sun) The&nbsp;Magners Bristol Comedy Garden will be transforming the charming lawns of Queen Square into a comedy wonderland featuring another mighty mix of comedy superstars. Join Britain&rsquo;s favourite pub philosopher as he serves up his unique satirical brew of ale-inspired acumen and bar-room buffoonery as part of Bristol&rsquo;s five-day comedy festival. Joining Al will be Stephen K Amos, Terry Alderton and Irishman Andrew Maxwell as host. Also on the bill earlier in the week is Milton Jones, Stewart Francis, Reginald D Hunter and more.&nbsp;More info&nbsp;here. EVENTS: St Pauls Carnival @ various (Sat) St Pauls Carnival returns with a new theme&nbsp;-&nbsp;&rsquo;Home &ndash; Inna We Yard.&rsquo; It is noticeable that the English language is one of the few languages that have two words to distinguish the place we live in &ndash; house and home &ndash; and that the latter is a very important one for all of us. The Masquerade leaves Portland Square at 12 noon, then heads up Dean Street, Brigstocke Road, Ashley Road, City Road, back into Brigstocke Road, the performers then divert and will reappear in Portland Square in front of the stage to perform their presentations. There&rsquo;s also live music on the Red Bull stage. Bristol Pride @ various (Sat &amp; Sun) The&nbsp;Pride&nbsp;theme We Are: Proud is the chance for LGBT people, their friends, families and the whole of the South West to stand up and declare they are proud of who they are and their loved ones. The UWE-sponsored event will see&nbsp;an exciting and varied mix of film, sport, talks, theatre and performance that will foreground and showcase LGBT performers, groups and causes. The Pride Film Festival is back at the Watershed and will screen the best in LGBT cinema, handpicked from the BFI Flare film festival held earlier this year. Films being shown include Lifting, G.B.F &ndash; Gay Best Friend and the acclaimed documentary Age of Consent. New for this year is the Pride Dog Show which takes place on Sunday 6 July and is the culmination of the &lsquo;Make Sunday Special&rsquo; event, which will see Small Street closed for a day of family activites and events. Brunch Club @ The Birdcage (Sun) This new regular event at one of Bristol&rsquo;s best small venue will see a great mix of food, music and fun on Sundays.&nbsp;Expect sweet music, brunch sharing platters and bottomless mimosas. Cure your hangovers the right way. Brunch Club will take please every Sunday throughout July at The Birdcage, from 11am-4pm. DJS Mr Belkin and Eggs, Kelly Kedgeree and Marting Brunchler will be playing the best in 70?s, 80?s and 90?s tunes. Food and drink includes&nbsp;Bottomless Mimosa, Bloody good Bloody Marys, Pick N&rsquo; Mix Tidbit Brunch with 18 choices of vegan, veggie, meat and sweet brunch canap&eacute;s Breakfast Pies w/ homemade bloody mary baked bean Posh Brunch Sarnies &ndash; all food is locally sourced , freshly prepared and seasonal.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.46186849325758','-2.5478236377239227',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00',0),
	(146,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristols Rise record shop teams up with Rough Trade','bristols_rise_record_shop_teams_up_with_rough_trade','Rough Trade invests in one of Bristolâ€™s best loved record shops, Rise, in exciting new partnership','Bristol&rsquo;s ever-popular music shop, Rise, has gone from strength to strength in recent years and continues to do so with an exciting partnership with Rough Trade.\r\nLondon-based international record retailer Rough Trade has bought into the Rise success story in a partnership which will see more stores opened across the UK, starting with one in Nottingham. Rough Trade, which currently has two stores in London and one in New York, also has pop up shops at UK festivals such as Green Man and End of the Road and&nbsp;at big European events, including Primavera and Pitchfork Festival.\r\nRise&rsquo;s MD, Lawrence Montgomery, has been appointed to run Rough Trade&rsquo;s UK regional operation. Rise, which was established in 2007, also has stores in Bristol, Cheltenham and Worcester &ndash; which incorporate music, fashion and film. The Bristol store is also attached to the Friska cafe, which hosts live instore gigs and events, including a very popular annual Record Store Day celebration.\r\nA Rise spokesman said: &ldquo;Our shops maintain the spirit of a classic indie record shop with knowledgeable friendly staff &amp; an extensive range of music on vinyl &amp; cd as well as more contemporary mix of complimentary products including our famous 2 for &pound;5 cult fiction range, our vintage clothing concession &amp; a carefully selected range of DVDs.&rdquo;\r\n&ldquo;Rough Trade defines the past, present and future of music retail like no other brand, so I&rsquo;m delighted to be joining Rough Trade during this incredibly exciting period, helping bring their much loved and respected form of music retail to cities across the UK, starting with Nottingham,&rdquo;&nbsp;Montgomery told Music Week.','','BS4 3EN','51.43084420127416','-2.5708589899658136',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 03:34:23',0),
	(147,NULL,NULL,2,'Hidden treasures of ancient Ur uncovered in Bristol','hidden_treasures_of_ancient_ur_uncovered_in_bristol','Food offered at the tomb of an ancient royal 4,500 years ago in what is now southern Iraq is among the findings made by academics in their own buildin','Food offered at the tomb of an ancient royal 4,500 years ago in what is now southern Iraq is among some of the strange findings made by Bristol University academics in their own department building.\r\nThe box, found in the Department of Archaeology and Anthropology, was filled with pottery, seeds and animal bones.\r\nIndex cards nestled among the objects, with keywords such as &lsquo;Predynastic&rsquo;, &lsquo;Sargonid&rsquo;, and &lsquo;Royal Tombs&rsquo; written on them, suggested the remains came from the excavations made by Sir Leonard Woolley in southern Iraq at the site of Ur during the 1920s and early 1930s.\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSome of the items found\r\n\r\nEnvironmental finds were rarely collected in this period, especially from this part of the world.\r\n&nbsp;\r\nThe collection will now be sent to the British Museum, where they will join the rest of the museum&rsquo;s collection from Ur\r\nThe original excavation was sponsored jointly by the British Museum and the University of Pennsylvania Museum, and the finds were divided between London, Philadelphia and Baghdad.\r\nDr Tamar Hodos, senior lecturer in archaeology at Bristol, said the remaining puzzle was how the collection made its way to Bristol in the first place.\r\n&ldquo;The environmental remains themselves were published in 1978 in Journal of Archaeological Science. The authors of that study were based at the Institute of Archaeology, London, and at the University of Southampton, and none of them had any known connection to the University of Bristol that might explain how the material came to reside here. If anyone can shed light on this mystery, we would love to hear from them,&rdquo; Dr Hodos said.\r\nIf you can shed some light on how the box came to Bristol, contact Dr Tamar Hodos (t.hodos@bristol.ac.uk) or Dr Alexandra Fletcher (afletcher@britishmuseum.org).','','BS4 3EN','51.449141604851725','-2.608624492895501',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 03:39:41',0),
	(148,NULL,NULL,2,'Councillors vote to demolish and rebuild Avonvale Road school','councillors_vote_to_demolish_and_rebuild_avonvale_road_school','Pressure from â€˜education emergencyâ€™ on school places forces committee hand, despite chair describing plans for new school as â€˜hideous and drabâ€','Councillors have reluctantly approved plans to demolish the landmark Avonvale Road school and replace it with a modern school to house 420 pupils in the area.\r\nDespite apparent sadness from most of the nine-string development control committee at the fate of the Victorian school, the &ldquo;education emergency&rdquo; in the area for school places meant no councillor could bring themselves to oppose the application.\r\nChair of the committee, Cllr Alex Woodman, abstained from the vote and said the plans for the new school were &ldquo;hideous and drab&rdquo;.\r\nCouncil officials lined up to support the plans yesterday afternoon at City Hall, saying there was no realistic way for the original school &ndash; built in 1898 &ndash; to be reused.\r\nThey said the urgent need for places in the Redfield, Ashley and Lawrence Hill wards meant that plans had to be pushed through.\r\nMeanwhile, local mother and campaigner for the school Amy Harrison said: &ldquo;We live within 400m of the site and there is black hole for school places in the area. This is the only way forward.\r\n&ldquo;The new school will make best use of space, it is the only site that addresses need for places in Redfield, out children deserve a high-quality learning environment.&rdquo;\r\nPaul Brand, the CEO of Educate Together the trust that would run the academy said the plans would mean the new school would &ldquo;engage with the look and culture and history of the local area&rdquo;.\r\nBut there was passionate support for retaining the building. Mariateresa Bucciante questioned how during the process of planning for the school on the site, officers had rejected plans to modify the building as it would &ldquo;affect the buildings&rsquo; historic character&rdquo;, yet would then go on to recommend full demolition.\r\nShe produced new plans from Bristol architects which she said showed a redevelopment of the existing school would provide more floor space for classrooms while avoiding demolition.\r\nCouncillors in the end appeared to be forced to accept the proposals, despite their reluctance to approve the plans.\r\nCllr Rob Telford said he had visited the site yesterday morning and said it was &ldquo;gut wrenching&rdquo; to lose the Victorian school &ndash; which had received support from the Victorian Society which made an official objection to the plans.\r\nCouncillors Colin Smith and Richard Eddy supported the plans, but Cllr Fi Hance tore into the argument put forward saying a modern education could not be provided in old buildings.\r\n&ldquo;It is rubbish that you can&rsquo;t have good quality education in an old building. In 10 to 15 years time, I fear we could live to regret this decision. The design is not good for young children, it is very corporate. But we are over the barrel here,&rdquo; she said.\r\nCllr Wright added: &ldquo;The best schools in the country, the independent schools, all have buildings centuries old. But the reality is you have to pay money to keep up the old buildings, and the state system has never been enamoured in keeping old buildings.\r\n&ldquo;I am not happy with what&rsquo;s before us, but we have no choice. We have an education emergency in this city. We would be pushing things back years if we reject this plan and we don&rsquo;t have years.&rdquo;\r\nChair Cllr Woodman said his &ldquo;heart said no but my head says yes&rdquo; on the application, but said before abstaining on the vote: &ldquo;I do think the new design is hideous and drab.&rdquo;\r\nCouncillors eventually voted seven in favour of the plans (Cllrs Richard Eddy, Fi Hance, Mahmadur Khan, Olly Mead, Kevin Quartley, Colin Smith and Rob Telford), with two abstentions (Cllrs Alex Woodman and Mark Wright). The first 60 reception class pupils will begin classes this September.\r\nThe main buildings will be demolished and rebuilt during 2014/15, with the first intake being taught in one remaining old building. At the start of the 2015/16 academic year, the existing and remaining pupil intake will move into the new building, with the last Victorian structure demolished to make way for the play area.','','BS4 3EN','51.40986272189464','-2.5302610743163996',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 03:44:18',0),
	(149,NULL,NULL,2,'Schools healthy lifestyle lessons â€˜had little effect on childrenâ€™','schools_healthy_lifestyle_lessons_had_little_effect_on_children','Bristol team say belief that healthy lifestyles can be taught effectively in schools need replacing by a more fundamental approach involving families ','A scheme in 60 primary schools in the South West to encourage children to eat healthily and be more active has had little effect on their behaviour, Bristol researchers have found. In a bid to educate children on healthy lifestyles, and thus prevent health problems including diabetes and obesity in later life, 2,000 eight- to 10-year-olds in 60 schools across the region were given new lesson plans and interactive homework activities. Teachers were given special training to implement healthy eating and lifestyle lessons in the Active for Life Year 5 (AFLY5) intervention, while letters and newsletters were sent to parents to inform them and encourage them to take part. But the team led by Professor Debbie Lawlor at the University of Bristol found no evidence that the work did anything to increase the time children spent doing moderate to vigorous physical activity, reduce the amount of sedentary time, or increase the amount of fruit and vegetables they ate. They did find though that children spent less time in front of a television or computer screen at weekends and also ate and drank fewer snacks and high energy drinks. The team conclude that, unlike prevailing theories that healthy lifestyles can be taught effectively in schools, a more fundamental approach needs to be taken across society and involving families far more. According to the World Health Organization, in 2010 three out of 10 children aged two to 15 were obese in the UK. Exercise for elderly pays off Older people who undertake at least 25 minutes of moderate or vigorous exercise every day need fewer prescriptions and are less likely to be admitted to hospital in an emergency, new research has revealed. In the first study of its kind looking at this age group, researchers from the University of Bristol looked at data from 213 people whose average age was 78. Those who carried out less than 25 minutes of moderate to vigorous physical activity per day &ndash; such as walking quickly, cycling or swimming &ndash; received 50% more prescriptions over the following four to five years than those who were more active. The research &ldquo;underlines that keeping older people active brings a whole range of health benefits, as well as reducing reliance on the NHS and potentially leading to major cost savings&rdquo;, said Professor Ken Fox from the university&rsquo;s Centre for Exercise, Nutrition and Health Sciences.','','BS4 3EN','51.47358020325013','-2.5415048945068293',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 03:52:08',0),
	(150,NULL,NULL,2,'Chair of governors at Bristol school quits after row over uniforms','chair_of_governors_at_bristol_school_quits_after_row_over_uniforms','Julia Skinnerâ€™s resignation was announced in the latest newsletter from Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, last Friday','The chair of governors at a school in Totterdown, who was embroiled in a row with parents over the controversial decision to implement a school uniform policy for children, has quit her post.\r\nJulia Skinner&rsquo;s resignation was announced in the latest newsletter from Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, last Friday.\r\nEd Plowden, who was formerly Vice Chair, has taken over her role.\r\nIn a short statement, the school said: &ldquo;We would all like to thank Julia for her sterling work on improving governance at Hillcrest, as was recognised by HMI, and we wish her all the best in her future endeavours.&rdquo;\r\nA row broke out in March over the school uniform policy, after headmaster Tim Browse set out plans to introduce a new uniform from this September.\r\nA vote among parents was taken in February, with a small majority (52%) voting against the plan.\r\nBut governors at the school decided to press ahead regardless. Ms Skinner said that because a majority of parents of children in the Early Years/Key Stage 1 age group voted in favour, the plans would go ahead.\r\nThe decision sparked anger among parents, with one mum &ndash; who spoke to Bristol24-7 but did not want to be named &ndash; saying the decision had &ldquo;left parents bemused&rdquo;.\r\nShe added that, for many parents, &ldquo;trust in the school is now at an all time low&rdquo;.\r\nThat anger was sparked again a week later after Ms Skinner published a blog which appeared to criticise parents for their reaction to the uniform decision.\r\nBristol24-7 understands that some parents were pursuing a complaint against Ms Skinner, claiming she had published information relating to parents&rsquo; confidential complaints on her blog.\r\nMr Plowden investigated the complaint and found no reason to support the complaint, adding that the school was &ldquo;lucky to have Ms Skinner as chair of governors&rdquo;, although admitted the school required a policy in the use of online media.','','BS4 3EN','51.431432828349585','-2.626734768164056',NULL,NULL,1,1,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:00:54',0),
	(151,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol Ideal: Schools project aims to tackle domestic and sexual abuse','bristol_ideal_schools_project_aims_to_tackle_domestic_and_sexual_abuse','A pioneering new programme for Bristol schools, which aims to reduce the shocking numbers of victims in the city each year, is launched today','A pioneering new programme for Bristol schools, which aims to reduce the shocking numbers of girls and women suffering domestic and sexual abuse each year, is launched today by the mayor, police and the city&rsquo;s MPs.\r\nThe &lsquo;Bristol Ideal&rsquo; project will provide teachers with lesson plans, guidance and support, leading to relationships and sex education lessons for every year part of the school curriculum.\r\nAn estimated 14,000 women and girls become victims of domestic and sexual violence each year in Bristol. The project, funded by Bristol City Council and the office of the Avon and Somerset police and crime commissioner (PCC), will set standards for schools to provide teaching on:\r\n\r\nDifference between healthy and unhealthy relationships;\r\nKnowing where to go to report abuse;\r\nHow healthy relationships are based on empathy, negotiation, and respect;\r\nAll forms of domestic and sexual abuse and about coercive and controlling relationships;\r\nUnderstanding gender violence as a cause and consequence of inequality;\r\n\r\nEach school will have a dedicated &lsquo;domestic abuse champion&rsquo;, providing specialist support for pupils, while staff will be given training provided for free by the Bristol Ideal project team.\r\nMayor George Ferguson said in advance of the launch: &ldquo;Bristol has acquired an excellent reputation for our innovative work tackling domestic and sexual violence, particularly around female genital mutilation, but there is no room for complacency and much more can and must be done. Time and money is always best spent on prevention work and I am delighted that this innovative project will do just that.&rdquo;\r\nCllr Brenda Massey, cabinet member for schools and young people, said that the project was a long-term strategy designed to change cultures. If done well, she added, it could have &ldquo;quite amazing results in the future&rdquo;.\r\nMPs from across the political divide are due to attend the launch and support the work being done. Bristol West MP Stephen Williams said domestic and sexual abuse was a violation of human rights and &ldquo;both a cause and a consequence of deep-rooted inequality between women and men&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;From preventing violence happening in the first place through meaningful culture change, to protecting the victim and empowering women, there is much to be done. We must be determined and fearless in shining a light on abuse wherever it happens, no matter how uncomfortable for the government or for society.\r\n&ldquo;Only by working together will we end violence against women and girls, enabling them to live without fear.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.456790100428265','-2.589999233496087',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:03:42',0),
	(152,NULL,NULL,2,'TV advertising campaigns against domestic and sexual abuse have raised the profile of the issue in the last few years','tv_advertising_campaigns_against_domestic_and_sexual_abuse_have_raised_the_profile_of_the_issue_in_the_last_few_years','Hillcrest Primary School embroiled in new row as parents opposed to uniform policy are described as â€œbulliesâ€ by chair of governors in now-hidden ','Fresh anger among parents at a school in Totterdown has been sparked following the publication of a blog by the chair of governors criticising their reaction to a decision to implement a school uniform policy.\r\nLast week, Bristol24-7 reported that the headteacher and governors had decided to bring in the policy at Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, despite a majority of parents voting against the plan.\r\nA vote among parents was taken last month, with a small majority (52%) voting against the plan. But governors at the school have decided to press ahead regardless.\r\nThe decision has split parents, with many saying the decision had left them &ldquo;bemused&rdquo; and that their voices had been &ldquo;ignored&rdquo;.\r\nBut anger was reignited on Saturday after Julia Skinner wrote an article on her blog in which she described parents opposed to the decision as &ldquo;bullies&rdquo; who were sending her &ldquo;aggressive, intimidating vitriol&rdquo;.\r\nThe article on&nbsp;The Heads Office blog&nbsp;was picked up by parents who took to a Facebook group, describing it as &ldquo;rude&rdquo; and &ldquo;bringing the school into disrepute&rdquo;.\r\nMs Skinner took to Twitter to ask followers how to make her blog private and, soon after, the entire site became password protected &ndash; meaning no-one except those with a password could read her articles.\r\nA copy of the blog was made though and posted online. In it, Ms Skinner said the school had &ldquo;made a bit of a dog&rsquo;s breakfast over the procedure&rdquo;, but said the reaction of parents was unexpected and unwarranted.\r\nShe added though that the opinions of parents opposed to the uniform decision would come &ldquo;where they deserve to be &ndash; much further down the list of priorities&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;We apologised for the bungled way we gave out the details but that did not stop the aggressive, intimidating vitriol that was sent through,&rdquo; she wrote.\r\n&ldquo;Hours of time have been spent trying to explain but basically they didn&rsquo;t get what they wanted so are furious and stamping!\r\n&ldquo;My life for the past week has been immersed in the anger from a relatively small group of parents. Terms like fascist dictator and corrupter of democracy can raise a smile when I read them here but when you are in the middle of it, it is scary.\r\n&ldquo;We knew there would be a reaction but I certainly didn&rsquo;t for one moment think it would be in the form of lengthy tomes, some of which were very articulate but all held that &ndash; &lsquo;you have ruined something special&rsquo; &ndash; element.\r\n&ldquo;What is interesting though is that there was no hue and cry when Ofsted came. Parents weren&rsquo;t enraged with the school for letting their children&rsquo;s education down. This has helped me put their opinions where they deserve to be &ndash; much further down the list of priorities.\r\n&ldquo;What support and strategies can schools get apart from being united in their resolve when those bullies are the parents?&rdquo;\r\nMs Skinner was defended by one parent, who defended her on the parents&rsquo; Facebook group, saying she was &ldquo;horrified&rdquo; by the behaviour of &ldquo;a handful of parents&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;She has had to endure an utterly unreasonable and juvenile stream of unpleasant abuse from people who should know better,&rdquo; the parent said.\r\nBut another parent, who did not wish to be named, told Bristol24-7 last night that Ms Skinner&rsquo;s blog was &ldquo;astounding&rdquo; and &ldquo;threatens to destroy what was a very happy school&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;When I read the blog I couldn&rsquo;t believe it. That the chair of governors who has taken such a controversial decision to overrule a parent vote and bring in uniform should then go online and call the parents who contacted her to complain &lsquo;bullies&rsquo; is astounding. It makes you wonder who these people are who have so much power over you and your children,&rdquo; she said.\r\n&ldquo;How insensitive can she be? This is an incredibly divisive subject and it threatens to destroy what was a very happy school. Parents are turning against parents online and in the playground and she should be focused on sorting this mess out. Parents are afraid to speak out for fear of being cast as troublemakers and who can blame them when the chair is happy to air those private complaints to the world?\r\n&ldquo;She showed no understanding or respect for parents who voiced their opinions. Instead she calls anyone who disagrees with her &lsquo;bullies&rsquo;, further dividing the school on this issue.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.46609493332001','-2.659264599096673',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:08:59',0),
