roversial decision to overrule a parent vote and bring in uniform should then go online and call the parents who contacted her to complain &lsquo;bullies&rsquo; is astounding. It makes you wonder who these people are who have so much power over you and your children,&rdquo; she said.\r\n&ldquo;How insensitive can she be? This is an incredibly divisive subject and it threatens to destroy what was a very happy school. Parents are turning against parents online and in the playground and she should be focused on sorting this mess out. Parents are afraid to speak out for fear of being cast as troublemakers and who can blame them when the chair is happy to air those private complaints to the world?\r\n&ldquo;She showed no understanding or respect for parents who voiced their opinions. Instead she calls anyone who disagrees with her &lsquo;bullies&rsquo;, further dividing the school on this issue.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.44555760313484','-2.543135677587884',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:11:34',0),
	(154,NULL,NULL,2,'Construction firm chosen to rebuild Ashton Gate','construction_firm_chosen_to_rebuild_ashton_gate','Barr Construction chosen for two-year redevelopment project that will transform the site into a 27,000 capacity stadium','Building firm Barr Construction has been chosen to redevelop Bristol City FC&rsquo;s and Bristol Rugby&rsquo;s ground Ashton Gate, the group set up to deliver the redevelopment has announced.\r\nThe two-year project will transform the stadium into a 27,000 capacity ground. In November last year, councillors gave unanimous backing to Bristol Sport&rsquo;s plans to renew the ground which designers said would turn a &ldquo;relic of bygone era&rdquo; to a &ldquo;beacon of growth for the city&rdquo;.\r\nThe development includes the demolition and rebuilding of the Williams Stand and Wedlock Stand, a remodelled Dolman Stand, and alterations to the Atyeo Stand and concourse.\r\nBuilding work is expected to be completed in 2016, with work on installing a new pitch already under way.\r\nAndrew Billingham, CEO of Bristol Sport, admitted it is a complex project despite the big ambitions.\r\n&ldquo;We want this stadium to be a beacon for sport and entertainment in the South West. Obviously having Bristol Rugby and Bristol City Football Club playing here from August will contribute to that, but we also have a vision of it becoming a venue of choice for conferences and major events.\r\n&ldquo;Bristol has been under sold for too long and it is time to build something that we can be truly proud of.&rdquo;\r\nBristol City FC&rsquo;s majority shareholder Steve Lansdown said in January the club would push ahead with plans to redevelop Ashton Gate &ndash; finally killing off proposals to build a new stadium at Ashton Vale.\r\nIt emerged last month that the club and town green campaigners have agreed that the northern section of the land &ndash; where the stadium would have been built and so bitterly fought over &ndash; can be developed into a sporting academy.\r\nThe southern &ldquo;wetlands&rdquo; area would remain registered as a town green which means no development would be allowed there.\r\nA report on this issue is expected to be put before councillors at a meeting of the council&rsquo;s public rights of way committee, possibly on June 30.','','BS4 3EN','51.42329840075612','-2.5651941645263605',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:13:27',0),
	(155,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol Rovers new stadium move delayed by a year','bristol_rovers_new_stadium_move_delayed_by_a_year','Failed judicial review and war memorial applications meant the new stadium would not be ready in time for the 2015/16 season','Bristol Rovers will not be playing at its new stadium until the start of the 2016/17 season, a year after originally planned, the club&rsquo;s chairman has said.\r\nNick Higgs revealed yesterday that work on building the new ground at Frenchay will not be delayed by 12 months.\r\nBut he admitted that delays caused by the failed TRASHorfield judicial review application, and attempt to get the entire Memorial Stadium site listed as a war memorial, meant the new stadium would not be ready in time for the 2015/16 season as planned.\r\nLeague rules prevent clubs from moving grounds during a season, he said.\r\n&ldquo;It is extremely frustrating that these small minority groups have been able to have such a massive impact on this project and associated projects that will bring so many benefits to the local area,&rdquo; he added in a statement on the club website.\r\nMr Higgs added that the fight against the judicial review and war memorial application had cost the club &ldquo;a lot of time and money&rdquo;, and is a fresh blow following the club&rsquo;s relegation from the Football League.\r\nThe chairman said relegation would not affect the club&rsquo;s plans to build the new stadium in partnership with the University of the West of England.','','BS4 3EN','51.41773190539157','-2.5427923548339777',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:18:45',0),
	(156,NULL,NULL,2,'No fairytale farewell to the Mem for Bristol Rugby','no_fairytale_farewell_to_the_mem_for_bristol_rugby','Bristol Rugby will begin life at Ashton Gate next season playing Championship rugby once again, after failing to overcome London Welsh last night','Bristol Rugby will begin life at Ashton Gate next season playing Championship rugby once again, after failing to overcome London Welsh last night.\r\nBristol played their final game at the Memorial Stadium &ndash; their home for more than 90 years &ndash; last night trying to overcome a 19-point deficit in the Championship final second leg.\r\nBut despite a stirring performance in front of a capacity crowd that saw them close to within eight points on aggregate, two tries in the last 10 minutes saw Welsh end up winning on the night 21-20 &ndash; and 48-20 overall.\r\nOutside half Nicky Robinson missed three penalties and two conversions on the night, and was replaced early in the second half.\r\nBut even with the 13 points which Bristol missed out on, they would still have finished 15 points behind.\r\nAndy Robinson&rsquo;s side finished the regular season top of the table by eight points, and undefeated in 13 games, but were convincingly beaten in the end.\r\nLast night, the director of rugby said his side had been left with too much to do after the first leg at the Kassam Stadium in Oxford.\r\n&ldquo;I thought it was an outstanding performance &ndash; the character we showed was excellent, but we were left to chase too much,&rdquo; he told the club website.\r\n&ldquo;We left a lot of points out there and had enough opportunities, but we have to be able to take those. It&rsquo;s something we will look at going into next season.\r\n&ldquo;We moved the ball well and had good balance. The commitment of the players, backed up by fantastic support, was very positive.\r\n&ldquo;Unfortunately, we weren&rsquo;t good enough in the first game and that cost us. This game is about inches and we missed out on those.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.406811041393766','-2.5934324610351496',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-03 04:20:46',0),
	(157,NULL,NULL,2,'Its official - Minister recognises Happy Lists as better than Rich Lists','its_official_minister_recognises_happy_lists_as_better_than_rich_lists','It was the first time in 7 years of Happy List publications that The Independent had gathered their happiness champions together, and the energy was f','<p>In a mad dash to London and back (which tested my happiness skills over 7 hours) I attended The Independent on Sunday&rsquo;s celebration of the national Happy List at the Grange St Paul&rsquo;s Hotel yesterday. Fittingly, there was another event for a large crowd of boozed up and suited City types on the top floor &ndash; I glimpsed it briefly as the lift took me up instead of down, and the atmosphere couldn&rsquo;t have been more different. The top floor smelled of testosterone, was roaringly loud, overwhelmingly white, mostly male and had the edginess of fast moving people and alcohol. Not a place for the timid. When eventually delivered to the basement, there was an entirely different feel. It was buzzing with conversation at a comfortable volume, crammed with all kinds of people from the very young to the very old, and incredibly welcoming as so many smiled in the direction of new arrivals. It too hot, but when people started fanning themselves, it was noticable that several also fanned those around them. Within minutes, I found myself swept up in the enthusiasm of Fatima Ayub from Bradford who&rsquo;s passion for looking after others by volunteering over the past 20 years was incredibly infectious. I was then delighted to meet Heather Wheeler, who gives free haircuts for people in a hospice up in Stafford. She&rsquo;d raised over &pound;20,000 for the hospice and we chatted about the huge potential hairdressers have to get people thinking more about ways of increasing happiness. The editor of the Independent Lisa Markwell, said how she&rsquo;d arrived in post as the list was published last year, and described the impression made by the Happy List as amazing and inspiring. It was clearly the kind of journalism which made her job feel really worthwhile. Nick Hurd, Minister for Civil Society, added his own fulsome praise about the value of the contributions Happy Listers make to society. He felt the Happy List was far more important than the Rich List and noted with a grin that none of the rich are ever really happy because there&rsquo;s always someone richer than them. It was the first time in 7 years of Happy List publications that The Independent had gathered their happiness champions together, and the energy was fantastic. Drawing attention to people who do inspirational things is clearly a very worthwhile thing to do &ndash; bringing them together is powerful in quite a different way. There&rsquo;s a sense of almost irresistable momentum about the way such a positive crowd invites others to step up and get involved. I&rsquo;d been invited because of the city based Happy List we&rsquo;d created in Bristol last year, and our plans to help develop city lists all around the country with in partnership with the originator of the idea, David Randall. Our discussions are moving on apace, and with another national partner with superb local community connections in the wings, we hope to be reporting on a string of celebrations from Truro to Aberdeen by this time next year. One thing&rsquo;s for sure &ndash; the Happy List has come of age. It&rsquo;s got the potential to shift the nation&rsquo;s thinking about what it means to live a &lsquo;successful&rsquo; life. Change that, and the world looks like a different place. Now that&rsquo;s powerful.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.452939269818536','-2.5769529688476496',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-03 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','0000-00-00 00:00:00',0),
	(158,NULL,NULL,2,'A weekend break in Marrakech with easyJet','a_weekend_break_in_marrakech_with_easyjet','You can fly to Marrakech with easyJet direct from Bristol, with flights on Tuesday and Saturday that are ideal to make a long weekend or short break','Marrakech is a destination that&rsquo;s full of exotic charm, where you&rsquo;ll be dazzled by the colour, overwhelmed by the hustle and probably return with far more purchases from the souks than you ever intended. Now you can fly to Marrakech with&nbsp;easyJet&nbsp;direct from Bristol, with flights on Tuesday and Saturday that are ideal to make a long weekend or short break. Here&rsquo;s our guide to all that you can enjoy in your long weekend.\r\nWhere to stay\r\nIf you only have a few days, you&rsquo;ll probably spend most of that time around the old walled city or Medina, so it makes sense to stay in a riad;&nbsp;a traditional Moroccan town house that would typically be home to an extended family and is built around an internal courtyard with a roof terrace for relaxation. Most riads are small with four to eight bedrooms, so you&rsquo;ll get the personal service and help of the Riad staff who can also act as your guide and concierge and arrange any extra services you require such as home-cooked meals or an in-house hammam treatment.\r\nThe most luxurious of riads can be hidden behind an unassuming doorway down a scruffy alleyway and they provide an oasis of calm when you return exhausted from sightseeing and bargaining in the souks. Check out the&nbsp;Marrakech-Riad&nbsp;riads and the luxurious Josephine Baker themed&nbsp;Riad Star&nbsp;where we stayed, or the&nbsp;Hip Marrakech&nbsp;collective, where you&rsquo;ll find a riad for all tastes and budgets.\r\nGetting around\r\nInside the Medina the lanes are too narrow for cars so you&rsquo;ll see donkeys transporting goods around or people wheeling wooden carts. Walk on one side of the street to avoid being run down by motorbikes and if you have an iPhone, you&rsquo;ll find the interactive GPS map on the free&nbsp;Marakech-Riad appinvaluable to find your way in the twisting alleyways.\r\nA fun way to go sightseeing is to take a horse and carriage ride around the outer streets of the medina to see the old city walls and gates. This can be arranged by your hotel or riad at a fixed price, or check the price with them so you know roughly what is fair when bargaining a price for one of the carriages lined up to one side of the main square Jemma El Fnaa. Outside the Medina a &ldquo;petit taxi&rdquo; is the best way to get around. These have meters but in the main tourist spots the driver will resist using them, so you should agree a price in advance and most shorter journeys around town should not be more than 20 Dirham.','','BS4 3EN','51.424047684896905','-2.608281170141595',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:42:44',0),
	(159,NULL,NULL,2,'Decision day 2 for Avonvale Road school demolition plan','decision_day_2_for_avonvale_road_school_demolition_plan','Councillors are due to decide today on a planning application to demolish a former Victorian school','Councillors are due to decide today on a planning application to demolish a former Victorian school in Redfield to make way for a new school.\r\nThe former&nbsp;Avonvale Primary School, on&nbsp;Avonvale Road, was built at the end of the nineteenth century but had recently been the site of Bristol City Council social services offices.\r\nThe application from the council&rsquo;s Children and Young People&rsquo;s department calls for the demolition of the landmark buildings, to make way for a new school to house more than 400 children that will help to deal with the chronic shortage of school places in the area.\r\nThe work on the site is planned to be completed in two phases. The existing western building will remain&nbsp;for one year as a temporary home for the reception classes of the new school, while the remaining buildings on site are demolished and the construction of a new school begun.\r\nThe second phase will start&nbsp;after completion of the new building, demolishing the western building and then constructing the playground.\r\nThe council says it has tried to retain the existing buildings but was unable to find a way to meet the &ldquo;educational needs&rdquo; of the children without rebuilding the school from scratch.\r\n&ldquo;While initially we felt that some aspects of the existing old school buildings might be worth saving or incorporating, we were also aware that the need for extra school places in the area is paramount, and we are pleased that the proposed design will make use of stonework and some of the existing walling,&rdquo; the council says in its application.\r\nThe pressure on&nbsp;the council to create new school places is seen as a key factor by heritage campaigners into making what they say is a rash application.\r\nAt a meeting with an officer from the council about the plans, campaigners tried to put their views across to local councillor Ron Stone but were given short shrift by the veteran Labour man who walked out of the meeting after apparently becoming angered by the campaigners&rsquo; refusal to accept that his sole point on&nbsp;the need to create school places in the area was the only relevant issue.','','BS4 3EN','51.44806971526446','-2.5890223681926727',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:35:09',0),
	(160,NULL,NULL,2,'Stanwell House Hotel, Lymington: A weekend away in style','stanwell_house_hotel_lymington_a_weekend_away_in_style','David Powell visits Lymington, staying at a boutique hotel, Stanwell House, right in the high street','Passing through Lymington last year on our way to Southampton after a lovely visit to the New Forest, I said to my wife that we must return and spend more time here, and return and stay in style we did with a short break at Stanwell House Hotel.\r\nLymingtonLymington is a beautiful Georgian market town by the Solent about 16 miles west of Southampton. It sits to the southern edge of the New Forest National Park and this area is a wonderful place to visit for a short break away anytime of the year.\r\nThe town is famous as a sailing resort with two large marinas and sailing clubs with an open air seawater swimming pool close by for those sunnier months of the year. For a small town there&rsquo;s a surprising number of interesting independent shops and at the bottom end of the High Street you can follow the cobblestone road that leads to the pretty Old Town Quay which is still used as a base for commercial fishing boats.\r\nSeasonal boat trips around the Solent can be taken from the quayside and private sailing and fishing trips can usually be arranged at short notice. If you want to venture further afield the Wightlink ferry sails from Lymington to Yarmouth on the Isle of Wight. However, needless to say, the many attractions of the New Forest are close at hand.\r\nThe perfect escapeOur short break to Lymington was relaxing and stylish with fantastic food &ndash; thanks to Stanwell House Hotel, a cosmopolitan boutique hotel situated in the high street. My wife and I experienced a warm welcome from the hotel&rsquo;s friendly, helpful team. Robert Milton and Victoria Crowe are proprietors and it was clear from their daily &lsquo;hands on&rsquo; approach that maintaining the very high standards of this hotel are a top priority.\r\nGuest roomsThe rooms at Stanwell House are all en suite and somewhere you can kick back and truly relax. All rooms have been individually designed with all the extras needed for a memorable stay and the personal touches certainly stand out. Rooms have complimentary tea, coffee and mineral water, direct dial telephones, 26&rdquo; flat screen TVs with a good channel choice, plus radio, trouser press and hair dryer. Complimentary WiFi is available in the rooms and public areas, just ask at reception for the code. Choose from Four Poster Rooms, Georgian Rooms, Suites and Garden Rooms which are also dog friendly! Some of the rooms are dedicated family rooms or adjoining and children are made to feel welcome here.\r\nI took the opportunity during my stay to have a look at a selection of the different types of rooms and they were all of a very high standard. Our room overlooked the high street, was tastefully designed with a separate sitting area and a spacious luxurious bathroom with a bath and separate walk in shower. And I have to agree with my wife&rsquo;s comment that the bed was one of the most comfortable she has slept in.\r\nDiningGreat food and warm hospitality most certainly, but so much more. From a great breakfast, lovely afternoon tea to a superb dinner dining experience. We dined in the restaurant at the front of the hotel for both nights of our stay. This restaurant is modern, airy, elegant, well laid out and a pleasure to dine in and has AA 2 rosettes for culinary excellence. Other awards include a hotel AA 3 star rating, the New Forest Marque for the use of locally sourced food and Trip Advisors Certificate of Excellence for the last two years running.\r\nThere are two separate dining styles at Stanwell House &ndash; Seafood at Stanwells and the Bistro. I chose to dine from the Bistro menu on our first night and Seafood on the second. The menu was extensive and the taste, quality and presentation were superb, supplemented by an excellent wine list. The service was first class and couldn&rsquo;t be faulted.\r\nSeafood at Stanwells takes advantage of the wealth of fresh produce available on their doorstep &ndash; freshly caught fish and shellfish prepared and served with the emphasis on flavour and quality. The &aacute; la Carte Bistro menu offers a wide choice of contemporary European food again of a very high standard and quality.\r\nBreakfast was a great way to start the day with a full choice of continental or the popular New Forest cooked breakfast. The hotel also offers an anytime menu with a variety of lunches, snacks, coffees and afternoon tea in the elegant conservatory just off the main reception area.\r\nDrydock is the name of the hotel bar at the front of the hotel looking out on to the High Street where you can choose from an extensive drinks and cocktail menu and relax on the soft and comfortable sofas.\r\nOffersSpecial stay and dine options are available along with seasonal offers and these can be seen on the Stanwell House website along with details of room upgrades and the five nights for the price of four offer.\r\nOut and aboutAs I mentioned earlier there&rsquo;s lots to see and do in this area and no doubt a trip into the New Forest will feature highly on your list. The hotel has their own Twizy car. This is an environmentally friendly electric two seater which can be hired for half a day or a full day &ndash; an ideal way to explore the New Forest as you can get up to 50 miles on a full charge. Bookings can be made at reception and the car is conveniently located in Stanwell&rsquo;s own private car park.\r\nAdditionally you could really push the boat out by chartering the yacht Indulgence of Lymington. This is a luxurious 40ft yacht, which can carry eight passengers plus the skipper and one other crew member. How about a lazy sailing day in the Solent with friends?. You can see images of the yacht and more details on StanwellHouse.com\r\nIf you&rsquo;re looking for a super break away from the ups and downs of everyday life and to &lsquo;recharge the battery&rsquo; then Stanwell House in Lymington ticks all the right boxes. This is a top boutique hotel and a great place to stay where there&rsquo;s a friendly welcoming team and sensational food. Stanwell House say their hotel is the &lsquo;perfect escape&rsquo; &ndash;I couldn&rsquo;t agree more and can&rsquo;t wait to return.\r\nFact file\r\nAddress: Stanwell House Hotel, 14-15 High Street, Lymington SO41 9AATelephone: 01590 677123Website:&nbsp;www.stanwellhouse.com\r\nThe price of a two-night, midweek break (Sunday-Thursday) costs from &pound;125 per person (two sharing), including two breakfasts and one dinner. Four-poster rooms and suites are also available. Well-behaved dogs welcome (&pound;15 per night).\r\nYou can see a video of Stanwell House Hotel that David has produced by visiting the website:&nbsp;www.YourHolidayTV.com','','BS4 3EN','51.4426688','-2.5683698999999933',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:35:40',0),
	(161,NULL,NULL,2,'Schools\'healthy lifestyle lessons ','schools_healthy_lifestyle_lessons_','Bristol team say belief that healthy lifestyles can be taught effectively in schools need replacing by a more fundamental approach','A scheme in 60 primary schools in the South West to encourage children to eat healthily and be more active has had little effect on their behaviour, Bristol researchers have found.\r\nIn a bid to educate children on healthy lifestyles, and thus prevent health problems including diabetes and obesity in later life, 2,000 eight- to 10-year-olds in 60 schools across the region were given new lesson plans and interactive homework activities.\r\nTeachers were given special training to implement healthy eating and lifestyle lessons in the Active for Life Year 5 (AFLY5) intervention, while letters and newsletters were sent to parents to inform them and encourage them to take part.\r\nBut the team led by Professor Debbie Lawlor at the University of Bristol found no evidence that the work did anything to increase the time children spent doing moderate to vigorous physical activity, reduce the amount of sedentary time, or increase the amount of fruit and vegetables they ate.\r\nThey did find though that children spent less time in front of a television or computer screen at weekends and also ate and drank fewer snacks and high energy drinks.\r\nThe team conclude that, unlike prevailing theories that healthy lifestyles can be taught effectively in schools, a more fundamental approach needs to be taken across society and involving families far more.\r\nAccording to the World Health Organization, in 2010 three out of 10 children aged two to 15 were obese in the UK.\r\nExercise for elderly pays off\r\nOlder people who undertake at least 25 minutes of moderate or vigorous exercise every day need fewer prescriptions and are less likely to be admitted to hospital in an emergency, new research has revealed.\r\nIn the first study of its kind looking at this age group, researchers from the University of Bristol looked at data from 213 people whose average age was 78.\r\nThose who carried out less than 25 minutes of moderate to vigorous physical activity per day &ndash; such as walking quickly, cycling or swimming &ndash; received 50% more prescriptions over the following four to five years than those who were more active.\r\nThe research &ldquo;underlines that keeping older people active brings a whole range of health benefits, as well as reducing reliance on the NHS and potentially leading to major cost savings&rdquo;, said Professor Ken Fox from the university&rsquo;s Centre for Exercise, Nutrition and Health Sciences.','','BS4 3EN','51.43870977297457','-2.5400457728027277',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:36:25',0),
	(162,NULL,NULL,2,'Holidays in Dorset: Why we found Hell, and never looked back','holidays_in_dorset_why_we_found_hell_and_never_looked_back','Itâ€™s such an idyllic location where there is an almost continual happy bird song; itâ€™s as if youâ€™re living in an aviary, writes Tim Saunders','&ldquo;It&rsquo;s not a place where travellers first think of staying,&rdquo; smiles Shige Takezoe who, with his wife Diana, owns Hell Barn Cottages in North Chideock.\r\n&ldquo;There are various stories about how this part of Chideock got its name. Some say Greeks came here and built a temple called Hellas, but this is disputed by local historians who say the Greeks only got as far as Devon. Others believe that Christians visited on a pilgrimage and made their home here.\r\n&ldquo;Then of course there was the Black Death where corpses were buried in the tumuli. Basically nobody knows why it is called Hell but it&rsquo;s a beautiful place,&rdquo; says Shige, who purchased the holiday business with its three cottages in 1996.\r\n&ldquo;It&rsquo;s very much an international business with 20% of holidaymakers coming from abroad as far away as India and many French and Germans regularly staying. It&rsquo;s only a 12-hour drive from Munich.&rdquo;\r\nI have driven through Chideock on the way to Devon many times and never really given it a second glance. Until now. And it is a beautiful revelation. A typical village with narrow country lanes that at times are so narrow it is scary especially when driving a large Range Rover, which seems to create its own lay-bys.\r\nWhat brings a Japanese man to this remote part of Dorset?\r\n&ldquo;Diana was an English teacher in Tokyo and we moved back to the UK. I haven&rsquo;t visited Japan since but my sister sends her children over every now and then,&rdquo; he says.\r\nShige taught Japanese at the University of London and then relocated to Newcastle where he worked for a Japanese company.\r\n&ldquo;I turned their loss-making office into a profitable one. It&rsquo;s only at that point when you&rsquo;re making money that you have the luxury to reflect on what you are doing. Realising that I wanted a better quality of life we moved to Dorset and found Hell. We&rsquo;ve never looked back.&rdquo;\r\nIt&rsquo;s such an idyllic location where there is an almost continual happy bird song; it&rsquo;s as if you&rsquo;re living in an aviary. There&rsquo;s no road noise and children are well catered for because not only is there a large garden to run around there is a slide and swings, which Harriett and Heidi thoroughly enjoy. There&rsquo;s also an enormous games room where we visit each morning. The children love playing in the Wendy house and we even manage to play poll and ping pong.\r\nWe stay in Rosemary Cottage, which has two bedrooms and a downstairs bathroom. Most importantly of all, the beds are extremely comfortable providing a good night&rsquo;s sleep. But it is only on this holiday that my wife Caroline realises that my snoring has been disturbing her sleep for the past three years. That&rsquo;s a tough day for me but I resolve to visit a pharmacist and find some anti-snoring strips, which help.\r\nShige cooks Japanese cuisine and delivers it to the cottages. He&rsquo;ll even take away the plates so there&rsquo;s no washing up. This is great because it enables tired parents to enjoy the restaurant experience at home without worrying about the children disrupting fellow diners.\r\n&ldquo;I also cater for diners in my home and sometimes they end up holidaying in one of my cottages,&rdquo; says Shige. We try the salmon and chicken teriyaki, which comes with rice, miso soup and salad with Japanese dressing. Until now I hadn&rsquo;t eaten seaweed but it was surprisingly tasty in the miso soup.\r\nAnother highlight of this holiday is our trip on the historic Seaton Tramway. We board at Colyton and enjoy a 30-minute trip to Seaton. Surprisingly we&rsquo;re able to fit our tandem pushchair on board in the open part of the tram. Admittedly it&rsquo;s a bit chilly at 10.30am but Harriett and Heidi are covered in blankets so they&rsquo;re happy.\r\nIt&rsquo;s a delightful way to travel to Seaton with breathtaking views of the River Exe estuary. We spot rabbits and pheasants. A thoroughly enjoyable day is spent at Seaton where we become aware that this seaside town suffers from a seagull problem. Interestingly, bird control comes in the form of a 246mph peregrine falcon named Morgan, who is a television celebrity. The moment he is released the seagulls quickly disappear.\r\nOur return journey to Colyton is much warmer. Travelling in this way is so much more relaxing than driving a car and having to look for a parking space.\r\nThere are so many attractions and places to visit along the Jurassic Coast, a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Venture down the road to Golden Cap and you will be richly rewarded with magnificent coastal views. From seaside destinations such as West Bay to Lyme Regis and Bridport, and just over the borders to Sidmouth in Devon and Chard in Somerset, there is never a dull moment.\r\nAt the Donkey Sanctuary at Sidmouth, 15,500 donkeys and mules have been provided with a sanctuary for life since 1969 when Dr Elisabeth Svensden MBE established it. The 400-acre site is home to around 350 rescued donkeys. It is open 365 days of the year and is free to visit.\r\nA la Ronde, the National Trust property at Exmouth is a spectacular 16-sided house. It was built by two wealthy cousins who wanted to make the most of daylight. The property enabled them to move around it with the movement of the sun. The same family had lived there from the late 1700s until the 1990s. Furniture includes a chair presented to them by their friend Lady Nelson. This chair had actually belonged to one of Lord Nelson&rsquo;s ships. There&rsquo;s a shell gallery and decorative feathers adorning some walls.\r\nWe finish our holiday at West Bay on a bench in the shade where we watch life pass us by.\r\nUseful websites\r\nwww.hellbarn.co.ukwww.tram.co.ukwww.thedonkeysanctuary.org.ukwww.nationaltrust.org.uk/alarondewww.chideockmartyrschurch.org.uk\r\nWatch the videos:&nbsp;www.travelwriter.biz','','BS4 3EN','51.424636399532034','-2.54347900034179',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:37:35',0),
	(163,NULL,NULL,2,'Chair of governors at Bristol school quits after row over uniforms','chair_of_governors_at_bristol_school_quits_after_row_over_uniforms','Julia Skinnerâ€™s resignation was announced in the latest newsletter from Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, last Friday','The chair of governors at a school in Totterdown, who was embroiled in a row with parents over the controversial decision to implement a school uniform policy for children, has quit her post.\r\nJulia Skinner&rsquo;s resignation was announced in the latest newsletter from Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, last Friday.\r\nEd Plowden, who was formerly Vice Chair, has taken over her role.\r\nIn a short statement, the school said: &ldquo;We would all like to thank Julia for her sterling work on improving governance at Hillcrest, as was recognised by HMI, and we wish her all the best in her future endeavours.&rdquo;\r\nA row broke out in March over the school uniform policy, after headmaster Tim Browse set out plans to introduce a new uniform from this September.\r\nA vote among parents was taken in February, with a small majority (52%) voting against the plan.\r\nBut governors at the school decided to press ahead regardless. Ms Skinner said that because a majority of parents of children in the Early Years/Key Stage 1 age group voted in favour, the plans would go ahead.\r\nThe decision sparked anger among parents, with one mum &ndash; who spoke to Bristol24-7 but did not want to be named &ndash; saying the decision had &ldquo;left parents bemused&rdquo;.\r\nShe added that, for many parents, &ldquo;trust in the school is now at an all time low&rdquo;.\r\nThat anger was sparked again a week later after Ms Skinner published a blog which appeared to criticise parents for their reaction to the uniform decision.\r\nBristol24-7 understands that some parents were pursuing a complaint against Ms Skinner, claiming she had published information relating to parents&rsquo; confidential complaints on her blog.\r\nMr Plowden investigated the complaint and found no reason to support the complaint, adding that the school was &ldquo;lucky to have Ms Skinner as chair of governors&rdquo;, although admitted the school required a policy in the use of online media.','','BS4 3EN','51.46042669773078','-2.5688848841308527',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:37:44',0),
	(164,NULL,NULL,2,'Feather Down Farm â€“ the perfect family getaway on Cheddar Gorge','feather_down_farm_the_perfect_family_getaway_on_cheddar_gorge','Itâ€™s camping, without being totally back to basics - the charm without the hassle.','It can be difficult getting away for a decent break when you&rsquo;ve got children &ndash; a long car journey or plane/ferry ride can be a bit of a mission and cost is a real factor for a lot of families; but there has to be a solution&hellip;\r\nThanks to the increasingly popular Feather Down Farm, there is. Started in the Netherlands 10 years ago and growing from a handful of farms in the UK to over 50 now, chances are there&rsquo;s one a stones&rsquo; throw from you and here in Bristol we have several choices, of which Warren Farm in Somerset is the best.\r\nSituated around 40 minutes south 0f Bristol and perched proudly on top of Cheddar Gorge, the family run farm is the stuff children&rsquo;s books are made of. The Good Life if you like and it&rsquo;s yours to enjoy a taster weekend of, without needing to commit to the downsides of living in a farm in the middle of nowhere! Beautifully crafted wooden/canvas tents, complete with proper beds, toilet and wood burner, are tucked away in a pretty field with free roaming hens (whose eggs you can help yourself too), some goats and piglets (depending on the time of year) and fantastic views across the Mendips.\r\nThe livestock farm, run by Kate and James with a little help from their two children, also has a herd of cows, sheep (and lambs in Spring) and a friendly dog. Visitors are offered a farm tour on weekends, ahead of a Saturday pizza night gathering with home-made pizzas (well self-topped pizzas) cooked to perfection in the traditional outdoor stone oven by James. You&rsquo;re invited to wash this down with all the local scrimpy style cider you can manage, and we&rsquo;re not talking a hairs on your chest apple beverage here, it&rsquo;s delicious and moorish.\r\nThe tent itself feels more like a cabin&hellip;until the high winds on top of the Mendips take hold, then, in a &lsquo;I&rsquo;m sheltered from the storm on the top of a mountain&rsquo; kind of way you remember where you are. It has a comfy double bed with a mattress, bunk beds and a very cosy bed in a cupboard &ndash; not as meagre as it sounds! There&rsquo;s a sofa and beautiful table and chairs, wood burning stove with chimney out of the tent, kitchen sink and flushing toilet. It&rsquo;s camping, without being totally back to basics &ndash; the charm without the hassle.\r\nIt&rsquo;s the perfect environment to relax, play some board games and enjoy a local Cheddar Ale, which you can buy from the honesty shop &ndash; that&rsquo;s right, the honesty shop, a larder full of delicious food and drink and other necessities which you help yourself to, keep a note of and pay at the end of the weekend. The Honesty Shop is situated next to the shower block, which is not your average campsite shower block &ndash; it has cubicles and hairdryers and, wait for it, heated floors. It&rsquo;s bliss.\r\nThe site is well placed on the Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty, Cheddar Gorge and The Mendips &ndash; as well as day trips into the Gorge with its caves and stunning scenery, there&rsquo;s the UK&rsquo;s smallest city, Wells, a short drive away; it has a fabulous weekend market taking place in the shadow of the cathedral and lots of places to grab a bite to eat. Wookey Hole is a popular haunt (apt word when you consider the Wookey Witch), but at almost &pound;20 a head it can prove a little to pricey for some (us included).\r\nA weekend with Feather Down Farm really feels like a break and despite being close to Bristol, feels like a decent Staycation but without all the travelling &ndash; great when you&rsquo;ve got little ones. Your Warren Farm hosts, James and Kate, are very welcoming and as parents themselves, totally understand how to create a family friendly, fun environment &ndash; but they&rsquo;re not averse to other groups and even offer up some barn space for parties when people book the field full of tents, great for reunions and other group getaways!','','BS4 3EN','51.4622428205879','-2.554260939359665',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:40:11',0),
	(165,NULL,NULL,2,'Controversial Dolphin School expansion plan approved','controversial_dolphin_school_expansion_plan_approved','Councillors approved plans to extend academy, despite concerns that proposed catchment area deliberately excludes children from poorer areas of the ci','Councillors have approved controversial plans to extend a school in Bristol, despite concerns that the proposed catchment area deliberately excludes children from poorer areas of the city.\r\nThe Development Control (South and East) Committee yesterday passed a planning application for the Dolphin School in Cheltenham Road to expand into the former Fowlers engineering site at Bath Buildings.\r\nAn extra 200-plus places at the primary school will be created, doubling the school&rsquo;s size from 210 pupils to 420 by September 2015, and responding to the chronic need for new school places in Bristol.\r\nBristol City Council provided up to &pound;4million last year for the school to expand.\r\nAt the planning committee meeting yesterday, councillors highlighted the potential for increased traffic congestion in the area once the school is extended, as parents from the outlying areas drove their children to school.\r\nCouncil highways officers acknowledged that congestion would increase, but the benefits of the new school were perceived to be of enough value to outweigh those fears.\r\nBut the school has come repeatedly under fire for its catchment area, which extends as far as St Andrew&rsquo;s, Bishopston, Westbury Park and Redland, but does not include nearby St Pauls and parts of Montpelier.\r\nAnd it emerged yesterday that the school does not intend to review its catchment area until at least next year.\r\nSpeaking to Bristol24-7 yesterday, former councillor Jon Rogers said his questions to the school about how they justified their &ldquo;bizarre&rdquo; catchment area had been repeatedly ignored by the school.\r\nHe said he &ldquo;could not understand why they being so intransigent&rdquo; on the issue and, while not going as far as saying the school was deliberately setting a course of social engineering, added he could not see any reason why the school chiefs wanted to pursue their policy.\r\n&ldquo;Bath Buildings is very narrow and so there is much concern about the travel and highways plan associated withthe planning application,&rdquo; he said.\r\n&ldquo;This is particularly acute because the catchment area is strange to say the least.\r\n&ldquo;Most school catchment areas are based on a circular area around the school, encouraging children within walking or cycling and discouraging driving.\r\n&ldquo;The &lsquo;area of first preference&rsquo; extended up to Westbury Park at the request of the council three or four years ago, due to pressure on places in these areas.\r\n&ldquo;There was a logic to it at that stage, but new schools have been built so that logic does not apply now.\r\n&ldquo;I cannot understand why they [the school] being so intransigent. I am being asked whether it is down to social engineering or prejudice or discrimination. Nobody is saying the school is being prejudiced, but now they are forcing through an area giving first preference to families in Bishopston over children closer in St Pauls.\r\n&ldquo;I can&rsquo;t think of any reasons why they would do this and the school should be explaining, particularly as it nearly led to their planning application being refused.&rdquo;\r\nDolphin, which as an academy can set its own catchment area, now plans to review its boundaries annually to take account of variations in the pattern of demand.\r\nErica Draisey, executive principal of Colston&rsquo;s Girls&rsquo; School Trust which manages the Dolphin School, defended the plans &ndash; insisting that 80% of the children live within one mile of the proposed new building, while 42% are from an ethnic minority.\r\nShe added a legal agreement to be attached to the planning permission, which now needs to be signed, will deliver a range of road and pedestrian safety measures locally, the final details of which first need to be agreed with planning and highway officers. The aim is, she said, to ensure the &ldquo;vast majority of the pupils will get to school on foot or by scooter&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;Naturally we are delighted with the outcome, as this decision should enable us to build a sustainable and innovative primary school in the heart of the city,&rdquo; she said.\r\n&ldquo;Our priority now is to sign up to the legal agreement. Thereafter we intend to consult further with the local community over the provisions and management aims of the School Travel Plan, whose intention will be to introduce a range of measures to encourage pupils and their parents to walk, scooter or cycle to Dolphin School.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.48309541608042','-2.6013288843749933',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:39:01',0),
	(166,NULL,NULL,2,'Are you finished?','are_you_finished','As strike action looms over staff pay, union said decisions made by universities to determine pay increases for vice-chancellors were unaccountable','Bristol&rsquo;s universities have been accused of refusing to release details of their vice-chancellors&rsquo; pay in a report into senior academic pay released last week. The University and College Union (UCU) said the University of the West of England (UWE) did not respond to a request for the minutes of its remuneration committee &ndash; the body tasked with determining the vice-chancellor&rsquo;s pay rise. Bristol University sent through redacted minutes of its committee. UCU said the decisions made by universities to determine pay increases for vice-chancellors were unaccountable and &ldquo;murky&rdquo;. The report comes as some staff at the two Bristol institutions prepare to take strike action, in which marking of students&rsquo; work will stop or marks will be withheld, from April 28. The action could prevent students from graduating and applying applying for jobs or places in further education. UCU said it wanted to discover why vice-chancellors got such arbitrary pay rises. Last year, the UWE vice-chancellor Professor Steve West received an 11.3% pay rise to take his salary to &pound;267,000. Professor Eric Thomas at the University of Bristol only got a 0.4% rise, although he still enjoyed a &pound;283,000 salary. The University of Bristol was one of the 27 institutions out of 139 that sent through its minutes. However, UCU said it was concerned that the vice-chancellor appeared to have had the final say on his pay for the year. Although the minutes say Eric Thomas indicated he did not think a salary increase was appropriate, the union questioned why a vice-chancellor was influencing the supposedly independent remuneration committee. On average, vice-chancellors enjoyed a 5% pay rise last year, while university staff were offered a rise of 1%. The UCU argues that staff have seen their wages drop by 13% in real terms since 2009. UCU general secretary, Sally Hunt, said: &ldquo;Millions of pounds of public money are spent on vice-chancellors&rsquo; salaries, yet their pay rise is decided behind closed doors with no accountability. &ldquo;The time has come for the lid to be lifted on the murky world of remuneration committees and senior pay in our universities. Students are paying &pound;9,000 a year to study for a degree and they, and the taxpayer, have a right to know why so much of their money is going on paying the vice-chancellor.&rdquo; UWE has, meanwhile, written to all staff warning them of the consequences of taking part in the potential marking boycott later this month. Talks between unions and vice-chancellors&rsquo; representatives are due to take place on April 15. In a letter to staff, UWE said any staff taking part in the action would be breaking their contracts and would have pay withheld. The letter went on to say: &ldquo;Such [strike] action could have a very serious impact on our students, including their ability to progress or secure employment, as well as on the University as a whole.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.48245400345847','-2.514124904882806',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:40:38',0),
	(167,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol Ideal: Schools project aims to tackle domestic and sexual abuse','bristol_ideal_schools_project_aims_to_tackle_domestic_and_sexual_abuse','A pioneering new programme for Bristol schools, which aims to reduce the shocking numbers of victims in the city each year, is launched today','A pioneering new programme for Bristol schools, which aims to reduce the shocking numbers of girls and women suffering domestic and sexual abuse each year, is launched today by the mayor, police and the city&rsquo;s MPs.\r\nThe &lsquo;Bristol Ideal&rsquo; project will provide teachers with lesson plans, guidance and support, leading to relationships and sex education lessons for every year part of the school curriculum.\r\nAn estimated 14,000 women and girls become victims of domestic and sexual violence each year in Bristol. The project, funded by Bristol City Council and the office of the Avon and Somerset police and crime commissioner (PCC), will set standards for schools to provide teaching on:\r\n\r\nDifference between healthy and unhealthy relationships;\r\nKnowing where to go to report abuse;\r\nHow healthy relationships are based on empathy, negotiation, and respect;\r\nAll forms of domestic and sexual abuse and about coercive and controlling relationships;\r\nUnderstanding gender violence as a cause and consequence of inequality;\r\n\r\nEach school will have a dedicated &lsquo;domestic abuse champion&rsquo;, providing specialist support for pupils, while staff will be given training provided for free by the Bristol Ideal project team.\r\nMayor George Ferguson said in advance of the launch: &ldquo;Bristol has acquired an excellent reputation for our innovative work tackling domestic and sexual violence, particularly around female genital mutilation, but there is no room for complacency and much more can and must be done. Time and money is always best spent on prevention work and I am delighted that this innovative project will do just that.&rdquo;\r\nCllr Brenda Massey, cabinet member for schools and young people, said that the project was a long-term strategy designed to change cultures. If done well, she added, it could have &ldquo;quite amazing results in the future&rdquo;.\r\nMPs from across the political divide are due to attend the launch and support the work being done. Bristol West MP Stephen Williams said domestic and sexual abuse was a violation of human rights and &ldquo;both a cause and a consequence of deep-rooted inequality between women and men&rdquo;.\r\n&ldquo;From preventing violence happening in the first place through meaningful culture change, to protecting the victim and empowering women, there is much to be done. We must be determined and fearless in shining a light on abuse wherever it happens, no matter how uncomfortable for the government or for society.\r\n&ldquo;Only by working together will we end violence against women and girls, enabling them to live without fear.&rdquo;','','BS4 3EN','51.472190174547094','-2.5779829371093683',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:41:48',0),
	(168,NULL,NULL,2,'Parentsâ€™ anger at â€˜travestyâ€™ over school uniform vote','parents_anger_at_travesty_over_school_uniform_vote','Hillcrest Primary School in Totterdown to implement a school uniform policy for children, despite a majority voting against the plans','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Parents at a school in Totterdown have reacted angrily to a decision to implement a school uniform policy for children, despite a majority voting against the plans.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Hillcrest Primary School, on Cemetery Road, is Bristol&rsquo;s last non-uniform wearing primary school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But plans set out by the headmaster Tim Browse in the school Development Plan for 2014-18 set out plans to introduce a new uniform from this September.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A vote among parents was taken last month, with a small majority (52%) voting against the plan.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But governors at the school have decided to press ahead regardless. In the latest school newsletter, Julia Skinner &ndash; Chair of Governors &ndash; said that because a majority of parents of children in the Early Years/Key Stage 1 age group voted in favour, the plans would go ahead.</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px; line-height: 18px; font-family: arial, sans-serif; color: #cd1613;\"><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Newsletter-7th-March-2014.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Read the newsletter here&hellip;</a></h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Management has now decided to bring in a uniform across the whole school by 2015, starting with Key Stage 1 this September.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The decision has sparked anger among parents, with one mum &ndash; who spoke to Bristol24-7 yesterday but did not want to be named &ndash; saying the decision had &ldquo;left parents bemused&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She added that, for many parents, &ldquo;trust in the school is now at an all time low&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;From the outset the school had made it clear that they&rsquo;d respect the outcome of the vote and many parents took to Facebook that night to vent their well articulated anger and disappointment at what many saw as a travesty of justice,&rdquo; she said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;That such an important change, ending a decades-long tradition of pupils wearing what the hell they liked should be communicated in nine lines in paragraph three of the school newsletter left parents bemused.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;The issue was always going to be divisive, as Headmaster Tim Browse acknowledges in Monday&rsquo;s newsletter. But he then goes on to state that a uniform will &lsquo;unite us&rsquo;. It&rsquo;s all very confusing for parents and children alike, but they have decided to push ahead with a process that even they acknowledge is flawed.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Mr Browse is very keen on uniform as it will give the school an identity. However he fails to understand that for the non-uniform voters the school already has an identity. He may see no value in it but the problem for him is that 52% of parents do.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;And for Bristol choice is gone &ndash; with Bishop Road Primary introducing a compulsory uniform in September 2014 and Hillcrest due to follow where does that leave parents who don&rsquo;t support uniform? In a Local Authority that bangs on about diversity it&rsquo;s a hammer blow to difference.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;I&rsquo;m disappointed in the result and would love to see the issue resolved properly &ndash; for the management to shelve the plans and run the process again fully in a couple years time.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;If they don&rsquo;t listen to voices they don&rsquo;t want to hear who knows what else they&rsquo;ll ignore if it doesn&rsquo;t fit with their vision or looks bad for Ofsted? That&rsquo;s my real concern.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;We voted, our voices have been ignored. Another lesson in democracy, local authority style.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Mr Browse said in a letter to parents that, while he though a uniform would be a strengthening addition to the Hillcrest identity, he had &ldquo;always stressed that the decision would not be mine alone&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;It was a very close result and I think it is right that governors dug deeper in order to make an informed decision that is right for Hillcrest,&rdquo; he wrote.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;I truly believe that they have made a decision that fits the majority of public opinion whilst being sensitive to the thoughts of everyone else.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/groups/605942212834043/\" target=\"_blank\">A Facebook group for parents has been set up by another parent</a>, with others venting their anger about the decision.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.482026390031855','-2.510005031835931',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:19:16',0),
	(169,NULL,NULL,2,'Watchdog rejects Bristol schoolâ€™s â€˜unlawfulâ€™ admissions policy claim','watchdog_rejects_bristol_schools_unlawful_admissions_policy_claim','Bristol Cathedral Choir School, due to expand into cityâ€™s Central Library, does not discriminate against poor families, report says','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A schools watchdog has rejected claims that the Bristol Cathedral Choir School, due to expand into part of the city&rsquo;s Central Library, discriminated against children from poorer backgrounds.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The Office of the Schools Adjudicator said yesterday the school does &ldquo;not discriminate unlawfully or discriminate indirectly on the grounds of socio-economic deprivation&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The adjudicator was brought in following claims made by teacher and campaigner against the move by the school into Central Library, Christine Townsend, that the admissions policy set by the school was biased against families who could not afford the transport costs associated with sending their children to the school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2014/01/06/bristol-cathedral-primary-school-free-school-can-afford-55377/\">Writing for Bristol24-7 in January</a>, the former Independents for Bristol council candidate said: &ldquo;How can an admissions policy serve the whole city if one family is able to access the school while their neighbours next door are not able to because they have no means of getting their child to and from the school gates?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She questioned how the school could claim to be &lsquo;open to all&rsquo; when its catchment area took in children from across Bristol and parts of North Somerset and South Gloucestershire.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2014/01/08/bristol-free-school-head-defends-admission-policy-14275/\">The head of Bristol Cathedral Primary School, Neil Blundell, defended the school</a>, saying the school&rsquo;s &ldquo;vision&rdquo; of providing a specialist music curriculum meant it would be a &ldquo;nonsense&rdquo; to limit admissions from a smaller, city centre area.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">He described Ms Townsend as part of a &ldquo;minority view among those who understand school admissions&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A case against the school was brought before the Department for Education adjudicator Carol Parsons, who ruled in favour of the school yesterday on the four main accusations, relating to its admissions policies.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">These included:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"padding: 0px 0px 0px 35px; margin: 20px 0px; list-style-position: initial; list-style-image: initial; font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Reserved and allocated more than 10% of year 7 places for its music specialism, for at least the last two school years;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Whether or not the school had carried out the necessary consultation exercises before making changes to its [admissions] arrangements;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Independence of the individuals who had overseen the operation of the random allocation of places at the school.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Mrs Parson did however point out other areas of the school&rsquo;s admissions policy which &ldquo;do not conform in relation to certain matters with the requirements relating to admission arrangements&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">These included policies relating to the admission of pupils with statements of special educational needs, the numbers of pupils admitted with aptitude in music and selection tests.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She added that the school had &ldquo;readily accepted some aspects of its arrangements do not meet requirements&rdquo; while other issues needed to be revised &ldquo;as quickly as possible&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The school&rsquo;s plans to move into the Central Library were boosted in January when councillors backed the mayor&rsquo;s decision to give the plan the green light.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The plans are still subject to planning permission and approval from English Heritage.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.49570803100469','-2.5848493921874933',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:19:01',0),
	(170,NULL,NULL,2,'Forest Holidays\'Deerpark \'the UK\'s answer to Yosemite\'in Cornwall','forest_holidays_deerpark_the_uks_answer_to_yosemitein_cornwall','Laura Williams enjoyed a weekend spent in a beautiful cabin in a idyllic UK location with family and friends','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Driving down the long, winding path to Deerpark, Cornwall, on a dark but dry March evening we had no idea what awaited us at the bottom of the valley (my co-pilot joked we were entering Deliverance country!), but as we passed the tall brooding trees we descended into a whole new world. A world of beautifully designed log cabins nestled in a forest of Christmas trees, a melding pot of wildlife and an inviting den of tranquility; it&rsquo;s really hard to believe this used to be a gunpowder works (more about that later).</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Deerpark, situated nr the delightful seaside town of Looe in Cornwall, is Forest Holidays&rsquo; much-loved South West retreat. Just a two and half hour drive from Bristol, it&rsquo;s a great choice for a weekend break and with cabins which sleep 2-4 starting at around &pound;350 for the weekend over the winter months (that&rsquo;s like &pound;20 per person per night with a full chalet of 6 &ndash; cheaper than some hostels) it&rsquo;s an affordable and thoroughly enjoyable Staycation. That said, we ended our weekend break thirsty for more and could&rsquo;ve quite happily stayed on for the week.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Just as our arrival at the site was a spectacular introduction to the world of Forest Holidays, from the moment we stepped into the cabin we felt the week&rsquo;s stresses disappear as we excitably explored our surrounds, as if we were kids again. Walking in through the front door on the first floor of the Silver Birch cabin we were greeted with floor to ceiling windows &ndash; revealing a balcony with hot tub, overlooking a lake and a forest. Positively idyllic.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The impeccably-designed cabins (which date back over a decade but feel wonderfully modern) are dotted around the site, almost camouflaged with the trees. Venture inside and you&rsquo;ve everything you need, from comfy beds, sofas and a fine dining table and chairs to a fully equipped kitchen, shower and a bath (ours had uninterrupted views from the first floor out over the lake too). There was also a game of Scrabble with the word &lsquo;WELCOME&rsquo; laid out. Nice touch.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">At times, Deerpark genuinely felt like the UK&rsquo;s answer to Yosemite &ndash; deep valleys, impressive trees, including a domineering Redwood, a beautiful lake and trickling streams. It is complimented perfectly by a stone building housing a village-style shop, complete with Cornish cider, local ales, fairings and other Cornish goodies (as well as all the essentials). It also houses a cafe, which serves delicious homemade pizzas, cream teas and more &ndash; all at very reasonably prices. And the staff are a credit to their employers &ndash; friendly and helpful, instantly making you feel at home.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Fortunately for us, we&rsquo;d inadvertently chosen the hottest weekend of the year to-date and enjoyed a weekend of Spring sunshine, but breaks like this could be enjoyed in rain and snow too &ndash; just in a slightly different way. The hot tub remains hot whatever the weather! And the cabins are sturdy and warming (thanks to a lush log burner). For us, we arrived on the Friday night and settled into a night in our home-from-home &ndash; hitting the sack early(ish) in order to be chipper for the obligatory 10am duck race.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The duck race is a firm favourite at Deerpark, with ranger, Martin, launching a bucket of rubber ducks into the crystal clear waters of the main river which runs through the site. With the help of his trusty dogs, he ushers the motley bunch of colourful ducks along as onlookers cheer and sigh (depending on the pedigree of their duck) and pray for a spot on the winning podium. It&rsquo;s a great way to start the day, partially because I won a bottle of Cornish cider &ndash; the icing on the cake!</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">There&rsquo;s always some ranger activities to take part in, from a bush crafts workshop to a two-hour history walk around the site (which also features the Lost Garden of Deerpark, complete with native daffodils in Spring) and a night vision exercise, exploring stars and constellations and bats and owl spotting with night vision goggles. You could happily fill a weekend with this programme, but Deerpark is located near a lot of attractions worth visiting; including the Eden Project, the coastal towns of Looe, Polperro and Fowey as well as Bodmin Moor. It&rsquo;s a great base from which to explore Cornwall and attracts a lot of walkers for that very reason.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The whole break took on that feel of a film &ndash; at times a hearty RomCom, all candles and romance, and at others a family vacation tale (think Dirty Dancing meets The Great Outdoors), series after series of picture-perfect moments and the kind of memories you cling on to forever. With no phone signal, 3G or 4G you&rsquo;re forced to unplug from the complex and demanding world or communication &ndash; which after the initial realisation you&rsquo;re not going to be able to instantly Instagram all the great stuff you&rsquo;re seeing/doing, works in Deerpark&rsquo;s favour and allows you to really relax. I mean REALLY.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Having never been in a hot tub before, I didn&rsquo;t really get what the big deal was. In fact, my only real experience of hot tubs was hearing my neighbours making the most of theirs every night come rain, snow or shine. In a suburban Bristol garden, overlooked by a bunch of houses including mine. Never really saw the appeal. But after dipping my toe in this pristine hot tub on the veranda of our magnificent cabin with its far-reaching views, I finally got it. The only downside is you&rsquo;re only supposed to stay in it for 20 minutes at a time &ndash; c&rsquo;mon!</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">We took this trip with a couple of friends (and two babies), but our neighbours included a couple, a 30th birthday party, a 40th birthday party (both had balloons to attest to this), an extended family and mixed group of young friends. To sum it up, it&rsquo;s a very versatile short break. In fact, while I was still there, I was looking up availability (using the cafe&rsquo;s wifi) for the Forest of Dean site for another break later this year!</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><em><strong>Deerpark in Cornwall is one of nine Forest Holidays sites in the UK, with others at the Forest of Dean, Blackwood in Hampshire, Sherwood Forest, Thorpe Forest in Norfolk, Keldy and Cropton in Yorkshire and Strathyre and Argyll in Scotland.</strong></em></p>','','BS4 3EN','51.43084420127416','-2.580987011206048',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:46:58',0),
	(171,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol free school head defends admission policy','bristol_free_school_head_defends_admission_policy','Neil Blundell writes exclusively for Bristol24-7 to defend the school, saying campaigner Christine Townsend is part of â€œminority viewâ€','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The head of Bristol Cathedral Primary School has defended the school against claims its admissions policy is unlawful.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">On the evening councillors backed the mayor George Ferguson&rsquo;s decision to allow the school to take over part of the city&rsquo;s Central Library, executive principal Neil Blundell defended his school against claims&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2014/01/06/bristol-cathedral-primary-school-free-school-can-afford-55377/\">made by campaigner Christine Townsend on Bristol24-7 this week</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She questioned how the controversial school, aiming to move into the city&rsquo;s Central Library, could claim to be &lsquo;open to all&rsquo; when its catchment area took in children from across Bristol and parts of North Somerset and South Gloucestershire.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She said families unable to afford transport costs to the city centre would inevitably be excluded from the school on the basis of cost, making the admissions policy illegal under education law.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">However, Mr Blundell has written exclusively for Bristol24-7 to defend the school, saying the policy was backed by the Department for Education. He added that the school&rsquo;s &ldquo;vision&rdquo; of providing a specialist music curriculum meant it would be a &ldquo;nonsense&rdquo; to limit admissions from a smaller, city centre area.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">He described Ms Townsend as part of a &ldquo;minority view among those who understand school admissions&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px; line-height: 18px; font-family: arial, sans-serif; color: #cd1613;\">Read the full text of Mr Blundell&rsquo;s statement below&hellip;</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Meanwhile, the school&rsquo;s plans to move into the Central Library were boosted last night when councillors backed the mayor&rsquo;s decision to give the plan the green light.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Last month, Cllr Richard Eddy and Cllr Rob Telford signed documents to &lsquo;call in&rsquo; George Ferguson&rsquo;s decision &ndash; the first time this has happened to any of his key decisions since he came to power in November last year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The procedural device meant the controversial decision to allow the Bristol Cathedral Primary School to lease two floors of the Grade I-listed library would be reviewed by councillors.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But last night councillors Tim Kent, Derek Pickup, Colin Smith, John Goulandris and Alex Woodman unanimously backed the mayor, merely rapping the council over its consultation procedures.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The plans are still subject to planning permission and approval from English Heritage.</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px; line-height: 18px; font-family: arial, sans-serif; color: #cd1613;\">Statement from Neil Blundell, executive principal Bristol Cathedral Primary School</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><em>We would like to respond again to the claims of Christine Townsend that the admissions policy of Cathedral Primary School is both illegal and unfair.</em></p>\r\n<p>Regarding the former claim, her opinion is, to put it mildly, a minority view among those who understand school admissions. Our policy has been approved nationally by the Department for Education. In the light of Christine Townsend&rsquo;s attacks, Bristol City Council education officers have also looked closely at it. Their report to last month&rsquo;s Cabinet meeting states unambiguously: &ldquo;The adopted admissions policies are legal and reflect the expectations of the Code of Practice on Admissions.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>It is true that Cathedral Primary School&rsquo;s policy is different from most council primary school admissions arrangements, in that we do not have a narrow geographical catchment area. But that is because we are a Free School and, like all Free Schools, we have a specific vision, well articulated through the application process with the Department for Education. At the centre of this vision is the creation of a school with an enriched musical curriculum, attractive to musically aspirant families who value the skills that the school is committed to developing. It would be a nonsense, therefore, if we restricted admissions to the area immediately surrounding the school: we do not want to exclude any Bristol children from having a chance to be part of this vision.</p>\r\n<p>Accordingly, we accept applications from children across Bristol and from BS postcodes in North Somerset and South Gloucestershire. Realistically, we expect the number from outside the city to be very low &ndash; this year, there is just one child out of 30 in our Reception class who is not from Bristol.</p>\r\n<p>We do all we can to help make the school accessible to families from different social backgrounds and we are proud of our ethnic and social diversity. We provide financial support with transport costs to families receiving free school meals (currently 23% of our children). And our central position means that we are perhaps the most accessible school in Bristol by public transport. In addition, some parents who work in central Bristol but live elsewhere find our location convenient and cost-effective, because they can bring their child with them on their journey to work.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><em>So is our policy unfair, as Christine Townsend claims, because some families have to pay for transport? No, of course not. The same applies to many other schools for children of all ages. Unless all children are to be forced to attend the school closest to their home, parents will always have to weigh up the pros and cons of logistics, whether schools are a good match for their children&rsquo;s abilities and many other factors.</em></p>','','BS4 3EN','51.484164417069294','-2.6397810328124933',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:46:16',0),
	(172,NULL,NULL,2,'Councillors set to debate \'call in\' of Central Library school plan','councillors_set_to_debate_call_in_of_central_library_school_plan','Decision to allow Bristol Cathedral Primary School to take over part of library will be reviewed at 5pm at City Hall','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Councillors are set to debate the &lsquo;call-in&rsquo; of the decision to allow a free school to take over part of Bristol&rsquo;s Central Library later today.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Last month, Cllr Richard Eddy and Cllr Rob Telford signed documents to &lsquo;call in&rsquo; George Ferguson&rsquo;s decision &ndash; the first time this has happened to any of his key decisions since he came to power in November last year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The procedural device means the controversial decision to allow the Bristol Cathedral Primary School to lease two floors of the Grade I-listed library will now be reviewed by councillors at a specially-convened Call-In Sub-Committee to be held at 5pm at City Hall.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Opponents of the scheme have claimed that the move, which will see the removal of the reference book-stock to B-Bond almost a mile away, will &ldquo;desecrate&rdquo; the prized service of Bristol&rsquo;s Central Library.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Meanwhile,&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2014/01/06/bristol-cathedral-primary-school-free-school-can-afford-55377/\">campaigners have claimed the school is failing to meet the law on its admissions policies</a>, failing to explain how children from poorer backgrounds will be able to afford to travel to a school which states it is &ldquo;open to all&rdquo; in Bristol.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The school and its supporters though say the school will provide some 10% of the acute shortfall in primary school places in the city, while providing &pound;60,000 a year to the council in rent.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Conservative councillor Richard Eddy said: &ldquo;There has been an abject failure to adequately consult over these controversial plans and to seek the views of service-users and other key professional stakeholders.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;We hope the Call-In Sub-Committee composed of backbench councillors will uphold the grounds of our &lsquo;call-in&rsquo; and refer the matter onto full council or the mayor for reconsideration.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Green Party colleague Cllr Rob Telford added: &ldquo;When this matter was last scrutinized by the Neighbourhoods &amp; Communities Scrutiny Commission in November, councillors had grave misgivings about the proposal and did not give the scheme their approval.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Nothing has changed in the intervening period and we will be working to convince the Call-In Sub-Committee that the arguments we have advanced demand that this major shake-up requires urgent reconsideration.&rdquo;</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.441384828837215','-2.4845991480468683',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:47:11',0),
	(173,NULL,NULL,2,'Grand night out for Gromit Unleashed at tourism awards','grand_night_out_for_gromit_unleashed_at_tourism_awards','Grand night out for Gromit Unleashed at tourism awards','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Bristol&rsquo;s Gromit Unleashed art trail has been named Tourism Event of the Year in the city&rsquo;s annual Tourism and Hospitality Awards.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">About 1.2m people came to Bristol last summer to tour the 80 statues of the canine superstar around the city.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">More than &pound;2.3m was raised for the Bristol Children&rsquo;s Hospital after the sale of the much-loved statues in October last year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Gromit Unleashed was among the winners at Destination Bristol&rsquo;s Tourism and Hospitality Awards, staged at Bristol Marriott City Centre hotel. The awards attracted 150 nominations.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Among the other winners were Horts pub in the Old City, which was named Pub of the Year, while At-Bristol Science Centre&rsquo;s ice rink scooped the Tourism Experience of the Year award. The winning organisations now go forward to represent Bristol in the VisitEngland Awards, taking place in May.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">At-Bristol&rsquo;s outdoor ice rink ran for eight weeks, and attracted more than 20,000 skaters.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">At-Bristol chief executive Phi Winfield, commercial and operations director Donna Speed and members of the At-Bristol team were on hand to collect their award.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Mr Winfield said: &ldquo;It really is testament to the hard work from the teams across At-Bristol, and a great way to round off a fantastic year. It&rsquo;s great to be recognised for what we bring in terms of tourism and hospitality to the city.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">In addition to 17 award categories, a special award went to Josh Eggleton, joint proprietor and head chef at Michelin-starred pub The Pony and Trap in Chew Magna, in recognition of his efforts to set Bristol apart as a prime destination for quality food and drink.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Josh launched the annual Eat, Drink Bristol Fashion event and devised the menu at Yurt Lush, a unique restaurant housed in a Mongolian yurt at Bristol&rsquo;s Creative Common.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Destination Bristol head of tourism Kathryn Davis said: &ldquo;The awards ceremony is our annual opportunity to bring together tourism businesses and individuals from the area and celebrate their achievements over the last 12 months. We had very worthy nominations in all the categories, and picking winners from such a strong field was a huge challenge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;It highlights what a great range of first-rate attractions, entertainment, eateries and accommodation we have in Bristol, but crucially it also recognises the efforts of the exceptional individuals that are behind them.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Bristol&rsquo;s M Shed won the Large Visitor Attraction of the Year category. Housed within a 1950s dockside transit shed, M Shed, which opened in June 2011, is an innovative museum for Bristol telling the story of the city through the stories of people who helped shape it.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Bristol Museums, Galleries and Archives deputy head strategy &amp; development Tim Corum said: &ldquo;A huge amount of hard work goes on behind the scenes at M Shed to ensure our visitors have a fantastic time &ndash; so much so, they come back again and again.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;And with more than 700,000 visits, it&rsquo;s really important our outstanding collections and exhibitions are exciting and stimulating and appeal to people of all ages and interests.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The awards evening also raised money for Wallace and Gromit&rsquo;s Grand Appeal, supporting The Bristol Children&rsquo;s Hospital.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The full winners list is:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"padding: 0px 0px 0px 35px; margin: 20px 0px; list-style-position: initial; list-style-image: initial; font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Bed and Breakfast/Guest Accommodation of the Year: Berwick Lodge;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Self-catering/Serviced Apartments of the Year: SACO Bristol Broad Quay;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Small Hotel of the Year: Thornbury Castle;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Sustainable Tourism Award: Noah&rsquo;s Ark Zoo Farm;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Business Tourism Award: The Bristol Hotel;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Tourism Experience of the Year: At-Bristol Science Centre Ice Rink;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Tourism Event of the Year: Gromit Unleashed;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Access for All: Bailey Balloons;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Taste of Bristol: River Cottage Canteen Bristol;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Large Visitor Attraction of the Year: M Shed;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Small Visitor Attraction of the Year: Bristol Ferry Boats;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Large Hotel of the Year: Hotel du Vin;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Pub of the Year: Horts;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Individual Award for Hospitality Customer Service: Peeradej Swetnant, Holiday Inn Filton;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Individual Award for Customer Service, Attractions: Pete Hayes, City Sightseeing Bristol;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Team of the Year, Hospitality: Housekeeping: The Bristol Hotel;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Team of the Year Award, Attractions: Groups &amp; Access Team: The Bristol Hippodrome.</li>\r\n</ul>','','BS4 3EN','51.44881859319405','-2.574259489774704',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:48:38',0),
	(174,NULL,NULL,2,'University staff in Bristol walk out for second strike','university_staff_in_bristol_walk_out_for_second_strike','Staff at Bristolâ€™s two universities have taken strike action this morning, as part of a national day of action over a continuing row on pay','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Staff at Bristol&rsquo;s two universities have taken strike action this morning, as part of a national day of action over a continuing row on pay.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Members of the Universities and Colleges Union (UCU), Unite, Unison and EIS are manning picket lines at the Frenchay campus of the University of the West of England (UWE), City of Bristol College and Bristol University&rsquo;s Senate House.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A rally to College Green is expected to take place at 1pm.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The staff are angry at a &ldquo;miserly&rdquo; 1% pay offer from employers, which they say represents a 13% pay cut in real terms since 2008.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">In October, university lecturers took their first national strike over pay since 2006.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The Universities and Colleges Employers Association, which negotiates pay on behalf of institutions, sought to downplay the impact of the latest strike, saying October&rsquo;s action &ldquo;caused very limited disruption&rdquo; as &ldquo;less than 5% of staff voted for industrial action&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">UCU regional official Nick Varney said: &ldquo;Staff in Bristol&rsquo;s universities and colleges are taking strike action to say enough is enough. They have seen their pay slashed in real terms since 2009 and this year&rsquo;s miserly pay offer, at a time of rising bills, was the straw that broke the camel&rsquo;s back.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Staff love their jobs, but their goodwill cannot continue to be taken for granted. Nobody wants to take strike action and lose a day&rsquo;s pay, but we feel we have been left with no alternative.&rdquo;</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.441170830133906','-2.615748440039056',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:48:06',0),
	(175,NULL,NULL,2,'Thumbs down from councillors for Central Library school plans','thumbs_down_from_councillors_for_central_library_school_plans','Campaigners against plans to hand over part of the Library to a new free school have praised councillors who gave the thumbs-down to the plans last we','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Campaigners against plans to hand over part of Bristol&rsquo;s Central Library to a new free school have praised councillors who gave the thumbs-down to the plans last week.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Councillors on the Neighbourhood and Communities Scrutiny Commission said they could not support plans to let the Bristol Cathedral Primary School (BCPS) take over part of the building.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">They said the plans left &ldquo;unanswered questions&rdquo; over the suitability of the site for a school, the impact on the building and on the number of school places required in the city, and the effect on library users of moving books to a warehouse elsewhere in the city.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Cllr Peter Hammond likened the proposal to a glossy estate agent description of a property which did not make clear the flaws in the property.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Independent councillor Jason Budd, part of mayor George Ferguson&rsquo;s election campaign team last year, said the proposal &ldquo;threatens a key part of the heritage of our city&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But the response from the councillors flew in the face of a recommendation to approve the plans by officers at Bristol City Council.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Meanwhile, in last week&rsquo;s budget proposal launch, Mr Ferguson said the city needed &ldquo;imaginative&rdquo; thinking to help continue library provision.&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2013/10/25/bristol-libraries-future-darkens-mayor-question-time-93913/\">He has already highlighted Brent council in London</a>&nbsp;which closed six libraries as part of multi-million-pound budget cuts.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Tory councillor Richard Eddy said in the wake of last week&rsquo;s scrutiny committee meeting: &ldquo;I am delighted that our detailed concerns have been taken up by the Scrutiny Commission and it shares our grave misgivings over the future of the library service if this move goes ahead.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Sadly, this hare-brained scheme does not stand up to scrutiny on library grounds, value-for-money or even the claimed educational merits of the case.&rdquo;</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.4478578156774','-2.592145000708001',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:48:55',0),
	(176,NULL,NULL,2,'Sandy Balls, New Forest: See how the other half live','sandy_balls_new_forest_see_how_the_other_half_live','Sandy Balls, New Forest: See how the other half live','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The most expensive of the national parks for property is the New Forest, according to This Is Money. The average house price in this part of the world hovers around the &pound;465,000 mark.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">As with many places though it is often better to visit for a little while, to get a taste of how the other half live, and then move on. The joy of travel. It is possible to do just this at Sandy Balls, the five-star award winning 120-acre country estate near Fordingbridge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">My wife Caroline and I needed a break after our most challenging year, which saw the arrival of second daughter Heidi Louisa, the start of our business and Caroline&rsquo;s dad having a pacemaker. In short, we were frazzled and in need of some relaxation. As I loaded up the car, I wasn&rsquo;t sure it was actually going to be restful though; the amount of luggage my wife and girls took astounded me. But after a few compromises we all eventually just about managed to squeeze into the poor car.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The New Forest is only about 40 minutes from home but it feels like another world regardless of the time of year you visit. We live on a busy main road and in contrast our luxury lodge at Sandy Balls was a tranquil retreat where bird song replaced the noise of roaring traffic and irksome neighbours. We had taken a six-berth lodge in anticipation of Caroline&rsquo;s mum and dad joining us. Her dad though was still recovering from his operation. But the extra room allowed both Heidi and Harriett to have separate bedrooms.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">We checked in at 3pm and soon after unloading, were swimming. At Sandy Balls there are two warm toddler pools and a main pool. We hadn&rsquo;t been swimming since July and it was surprising to see Harriett with her armbands on doing backstroke as soon as she touched the water.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">It would be very easy to stay at the large holiday park and not venture outside because it has its own well-stocked country store, launderette, gym, sauna, pub and restaurant. Pizza in the Piazza offers good quality food in bright and convivial surroundings. It really does provide a welcome break from the baked beans and scrambled eggs typical of Saunders self catering.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Instead we savoured homemade smoked haddock fishcakes followed by duck with plum and red wine sauce accompanied by a pleasant Italian red. A dessert of chocolate fudge cake and a cappuccino to finish was certainly a pleasing treat. So often these days restaurant service leaves much to be desired but at Pizza in the Piazza the staff were cheerful and genuinely interested in their customers. All cutlery and glasses were gleaming, too.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Each night we all slept well on the comfy beds apart from the first night when Harriett fell out of hers. Our lodge coped well with the winter weather, the combination boiler keeping it warm and cosy.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The onsite cycle centre had a host of bicycles available for hire. We opted for a couple of comfort bikes providing upright riding and I towed the trailer with Harriett and Heidi inside. They enjoyed it and Heidi even fell asleep at one point. We toured the surrounding areas of Stuckton and Gorley. Even though we opted for the quickest route, the hills on the return leg really slowed us up and we failed to cover the distance in the suggested time. In parts I had to get off and push because I did not have the strength to pedal uphill with the loaded trailer.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">On our travels we saw New Forest ponies and donkeys freely roaming by the roadside and sometimes in it; a very useful traffic calming measure although slightly tricky to negotiate on two wheels. Road accidents involving these creatures are on the rise. A total of 65 animals were killed or injured between January 1 and the end of September 2013, compared with 50 in the same period last year, so caution is required when driving through the Forest.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Just down the road is Fordingbridge, a quaint market town famous for its Great Bridge, with its seven graceful arches. There is also a statue of its most famous inhabitant, Augustus John, the portrait painter. Harriett and Heidi enjoyed playing on the swings and slides there.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">We returned home more relaxed than we have been for some time after spending quality time together as a family.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Those who have fallen in love with the New Forest after their stay might like to know that it is much cheaper to buy a slice than estate agents would have you believe. Vista Lodges at Sandy Balls start from just &pound;17,250 for a share of a lodge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><strong>Facts at a glance</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Holiday prices start from just &pound;129 for two people staying off peak rising to &pound;1,549 for six people at peak times.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><strong>Recommendations</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Enjoy a meal at Pizza in the Piazza</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Have a daily swim in the indoor heated pool</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Hire a bike and cycle through the New Forest</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><strong>Places to avoid</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">There are a number of over-priced pubs and restaurants in the New Forest that overcharge and under deliver. Far better to eat at Sandy Balls where good quality food is competitively priced.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><strong>For more information visit</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\"><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.sandyballs.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\">www.sandyballs.co.uk</a><br /><a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.sandyballshomes.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\">www.sandyballshomes.co.uk</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Watch the video at&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.travelwriter.biz/\" target=\"_blank\">www.travelwriter.biz</a></p>','','BS4 3EN','51.50703503232923','-2.598238979589837',NULL,NULL,1,0,1,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:50:48',0),
	(177,NULL,NULL,2,'Ferguson ally urges rethink over Central Library school plan','ferguson_ally_urges_rethink_over_central_library_school_plan','Cllr Jason Budd, part of Mr Fergusonâ€™s election campaign, said proposal â€œthreatens a key part of the heritage of our cityâ€','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A close ally of George Ferguson has urged the Bristol mayor not to hand over part of the city&rsquo;s historic Central Library to a free school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Independent councillor Jason Budd was part of Mr Ferguson&rsquo;s election campaign team last year. He said the proposal to let the Bristol Cathedral Primary School (BCPS) take over part of the building &ldquo;threatens a key part of the heritage of our city&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">He added he was &ldquo;disappointed&rdquo; with the mayor for considering the plan and called on him to think again.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Of course new primary school places are needed in Bristol, and indeed I support the principle of using old spaces in new ways,&rdquo; Cllr Budd said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;But this proposal threatens a key part of the heritage of our city and it is future generations not yet born who will suffer the consequences, all for the short term gain of 30 extra school places.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;I am disappointed in the mayor for considering such a proposal, and ask him to think again.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The statement comes as councillors on the Neighbourhood and Communities Scrutiny Commission prepare to examine the plans in detail this afternoon.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Hopes to prevent BCPS taking over two floors of the library as a permanent home were dashed last week when it emerged officers at Bristol City Council (BCC) had recommended the plans for approval.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Robert Orrett, the Strategic Property Service Director at BCC, said in a report for councillors that the plans would provide new school places for the city at no extra cost to the council, and an additional funding stream from the rent paid by the new school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The proposals include:</p>\r\n<ul style=\"padding: 0px 0px 0px 35px; margin: 20px 0px; list-style-position: initial; list-style-image: initial; font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">125-year lease to BCPS/Education Funding Agency;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">A right to break the lease every 25 years;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Rent from BCPS at a minimum &pound;50,000 a year;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Premium of &pound;600,000 for switchover costs;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Education Funding Agency to be responsible for cost and delivery of all works at Central Library<br />building;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Council to manage the creation of new book store with an improved online catalogue, with<br />funding from the negotiated premium;</li>\r\n<li style=\"padding: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; list-style: disc;\">Cathedral Primary School/Education Funding Agency to pay 20% of costs for maintaining<br />structure exterior of Central Library building up to &pound;10,000 per annum.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But campaigners against the plans will take their battle to the council watchdog this afternoon.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Cllr Richard Eddy, former chairman of the all-party Libraries Select Committee, who has launched his own e-petition against the proposal, said there had been an &ldquo;astonishing &lsquo;democratic deficit&rsquo;, which has been discussed in secret with Bristol Cathedral Choir School since before Christmas last year&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Despite meetings with the Mayor and the Cabinet Member for Leisure &amp; Libraries, campaigners have discovered that there are more questions than answers over the proposal,&rdquo; he added.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;We hope that the Neighbourhoods and Communities Scrutiny Commission will properly study the plan on Wednesday afternoon and subject it to serious scrutiny.&rdquo;</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.43673013076665','-2.5571260798095636',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:50:05',0),
	(178,NULL,NULL,2,'\'Outrage\' at defeat over qualified teachers plan for free schools','outrage_at_defeat_over_qualified_teachers_plan_for_free_schools','Thangam Debbonaire, Labour parliamentary candidate for Bristol West, said highest quality education meant skilled, trained teachers','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A Labour parliamentary candidate has spoken of her outrage that a bid to ensure all free school and academy teachers are fully qualified failed to be passed in Parliament.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Thangam Debbonaire, Labour parliamentary candidate for Bristol West, repeated her shadow education secretary&rsquo;s claim that managers at McDonald&rsquo;s require more qualifications than teachers under Michael Gove&rsquo;s flagship free schools scheme.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Labour claims that academies and Free Schools now have the lowest requirements for teacher qualifications in the world, with more than 5,000 unqualified teachers now employed in Britain.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Tristram Hunt said the &ldquo;wholesale deregulation&rdquo; of schools had undermined teachers and would drive down standards.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But a Labour motion, to force all teachers to have a minimum standard of qualifications, was defeated by 263 to 229 in the House of Commons despite only one Liberal Democrat voting with the Government.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;As a school governor and with family educated at local state schools I am outraged. Our children need the highest possible quality of education to be able to take the technological, creative and scientific jobs of the future and this means skilled, trained teachers,&rdquo; Ms Debbonaire said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;The evidence from the highest performing in education overseas countries is clear, for example in Finland all teachers must earn a Master&rsquo;s degree.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">David Laws, the Liberal Democrat schools minister, spoke in defence of Mr Gove&rsquo;s policy in the Commons, before abstaining on the vote. Stephen Williams, Ms Debbonaire&rsquo;s rival for the Bristol West seat, also abstained.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.44464818482021','-2.58742431284179',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:18:43',0),
	(179,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol University staff prepare to strike over pay','bristol_university_staff_prepare_to_strike_over_pay','Members of the University and College Union (UCU) and Unison are preparing to take their first ever coordinated strike action in a row over pay','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Staff at Bristol University will go on strike tomorrow unless last-ditch talks with their employers take place.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Members of the University and College Union (UCU) and Unison are preparing to take their first ever coordinated strike action in a row over pay.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The unions have rejected a pay offer of 1% which they say represents a 13% pay cut in real terms since 2008.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The unions say they are willing to meet for last-minute talks but say they are not optimistic &ldquo;as the employers had so far refused to engage in talks aimed at resolving the dispute&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">President of Bristol UCU, Professor James Annett, said: &ldquo;Staff at the University of Bristol are angry they&rsquo;ve had to endure massive pay cuts in recent years. This year&rsquo;s miserly 1% pay offer, at a time of rising bills and increased pension contributions, was the straw that broke the camel&rsquo;s back.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Staff love their jobs, but their goodwill cannot continue to be taken for granted.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">TUC general secretary Frances O&rsquo;Grady added: &ldquo;Nobody wants to see disruption in our universities, but staff have had to endure one of the most sustained pay squeezes since the Second World War and understandably are very angry. Rather than refusing to meet the unions, the employers should be getting around the table for talks to try and find a fair resolution to this dispute.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A spokesman for the Universities and Colleges Employers Association (UCEA) said that less than 5% of the higher education workforce had chosen to vote in favour of strike action and predicted &ldquo;a low level impact on students&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The spokesman said that they had made their final pay offer in May and had been engaged in a dispute resolution process with the unions throughout the summer.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.439886816856756','-2.5950632441162043',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:51:52',0),
	(180,NULL,NULL,2,'Review: The very capable and enjoyable Nissan Juke','review_the_very_capable_and_enjoyable_nissan_juke','Eye-catching design at an attractive price. That is the combination on offer from Nissan with its Juke','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Eye-catching design at an attractive price. That is the combination on offer from Nissan with its Juke, the increasingly fashionable compact sports utility vehicle. There is no denying it, it is a great design that from a distance looks like a three-door but thanks to cleverly concealed rear door handles it is actually a five-door vehicle.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">For under &pound;15,000 excluding VAT it represents extremely good value for money, too.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">It seems to appeal to all generations from the young girl who cycles past and tells her dad how she likes it, through to the middle-aged man who simply stands and stares and the gentleman of senior years who I spot driving his in Weymouth.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Arguably the brown finish of the test vehicle really does lend itself to the design although I feel that cream leather upholstery would compliment this particularly well. As it is, the black cloth seats are comfortable even over a fairly long journey from Hampshire to Dorset.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The raised ride height is always a welcome bonus for me because it gives greater command of the road. It also allows the driver to spot parking spaces that others do not in packed car parks. I find the 1.5 diesel unit pleasantly poky at speeds under 60mph with third gear being very receptive between 30mph and 60mph.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Over that speed it proves slower than expected and at times struggles to hold its own while in the outside lane of the motorway. Hills slow it up a bit requiring a change down to fourth gear but it is only a 1.5 litre and a diesel and so overall it does a good job. With hard driving it will return over 40mpg. The best recorded was around 47mpg.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Perhaps surprisingly the Juke really does hold the road and feels like it is on rails when cornering, meaning that it can be driven with gusto even round bends. Rather than simply being an attractive head-turner it is also pleasingly a driver&rsquo;s car helped by the fairly hard suspension.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The n-tec model tested also comes fitted with cruise control which is useful for motorway cruising. The test takes place just after the UK has been badly battered by storms and the Juke copes with the floods admirably. Just down the road from my parents in law there is an enormous flood that has previously shut the road but the Juke makes light work of it.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Reversing the Juke is made easier by the camera display on the dashboard. Without that it would be a little tricky due to the design of the rear.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">While we&rsquo;re talking about the rear, it looks a little awkward to me, there is something that could be improved about it but I can&rsquo;t quite put my finger on it. Head on and the side profile both get a firm 10 out of 10 but the rear gets eight.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Inside is well equipped with all round electric windows, air conditioning and sat nav as you can see in the video at testdrives.biz. I also like the bulbous chrome door handles. There is enough room inside for four or five occupants to be comfortable and the boot is large enough for a pushchair.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A very capable and enjoyable SUV.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.49875377505607','-2.687331234228509',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:53:34',0),
	(181,NULL,NULL,2,'Central Library campaigners must\'get real\', says free school head','central_library_campaigners_must_get_real_says_free_school_head','Robust defence of plans as it emerges nearly Â£4million will be spent by central government to help fund conversion of building','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Nearly &pound;4million will be spent by central government to help a free school move into Bristol&rsquo;s Central Library, it has emerged.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Bristol Cathedral Primary School (BCPS) &ndash; one of the government&rsquo;s flagship free schools &ndash; wants to use the lower two floors of the library as a permanent home.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But the move has proved controversial with campaigners angry at the impact it will have on library provision in the city.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Now the school and Bristol City Council have produced a question-and-answer document in which they provide more details of the plans.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Meanwhile, the school&rsquo;s executive principal has called on campaigners against the plans to let parents make up their own minds as to whether the lower floors of the library will be suitable as classrooms.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Neil Blundell said campaigners needed to &ldquo;get real&rdquo; about the issue of primary school places facing Bristol. He added that criticism about the lack of natural light available to the space where the school would sit had not put off parents, saying they were &ldquo;voting with their feet&rdquo; by applying for places at the school.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">According to the school, the total cost of works at the library is estimated at &pound;3.8m &ndash; with all funds coming from government agency the Education Funding Authority.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The cost of moving books from the library to a new site, expected to be at Cumberland Basin, and catalogue them online is is expected to be up to &pound;600,000 on its own.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">There is also expected to be &ldquo;disruption for a period of time to the core Central Library Service&rdquo; during the works to refit the two floors for school use.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">However, they insist there will be no change to the Lending Library. &ldquo;All public space in the<br />Central Library will remain as such,&rdquo; the document says.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The city council is keen to see the plans go ahead, as the school would create much-needed primary school places and extra income of about &pound;45,000 a year.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Mr Blundell said in a separate statement that sister school the Bristol Cathedral Choir School (BCCS) had experience of working with the buildings in the area and that the work to convert the Central Library would mean it was suitable for education.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;I think we need to get real in this debate &ndash; real about the financial pressures facing local authorities and real, too, about the use of historic buildings as schools,&rdquo; he said.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;It is true that, in an ideal world, we would welcome a little extra natural light in some of the mediaeval rooms at BCCS, but that doesn&rsquo;t mean they are unsuitable for education.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;The truth is that children are influenced by architecture and place, inspired often by the classrooms and the view beyond. We know that children love the older part of the campus.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;We are confident that parents and children will find any slight lack of natural illumination amply compensated by the prospect of working in such a magnificent building and in such close proximity to BCCS facilities and, of course, to the cathedral. These lower floors have the potential to become a wonderful primary school, capable of providing an outstanding education to future generations of Bristol children.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;In fact, with still more than three months to go before applications close for next year&rsquo;s Cathedral Primary School places, we have already been overwhelmed with interest from families: whatever the protesters may say about our proposal, it seems the parents of Bristol are voting with their feet.&rdquo;</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.44111733030139','-2.6087103235839777',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:18:27',0),
	(182,NULL,NULL,2,'Teachers head for Bristol rally as school strike begins','teachers_head_for_bristol_rally_as_school_strike_begins','..........     Filed in: Education, NEWS   Teachers head for Bristol rally as school strike begins Thousands of school teachers are expected for a ral','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Thousands of school teachers are expected for a rally in Bristol today to mark a national day of action over pay, pensions and jobs.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Teachers across the West Country are joining colleagues from the NUT and NASUWT unions in London, Cumbria, the South East and North East in the one-day strike.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The action is being taken against proposals by Education Secretary Michael Gove to bring in performance-related pay, increase teachers&rsquo; workloads and make changes to their pensions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">NUT general secretary Christine Blower said it regretted the disruption caused to pupils and parents but teachers felt they had &ldquo;no other choice&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;The NUT sincerely regrets the disruption that will be caused by strike action on Thursday for children and parents,&rdquo; she said in a statement. &ldquo;Teachers, however, feel they have no other choice to demonstrate their concerns about the Government&rsquo;s proposals.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">She added that Mr Gove had &ldquo;done nothing to address the crisis of low morale in the teaching profession&rdquo;, while changes to pay, pensions and conditions would &ldquo;make it harder for your child&rsquo;s school to recruit and retain good teachers&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Meanwhile, Mike Harrison, Wiltshire secretary of the NUT,&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.gazetteandherald.co.uk/news/towns/wiltshire/10741992.Strike_action_closes_Wiltshire_schools_as_teachers_urged_to_join_Bristol_rally/\" target=\"_blank\">told the Gazette and Herald newspaper</a>: &ldquo;We are striking together with the NASUWT in Bristol, which we have never done before. Michael Gove has done wonders in uniting the two unions and it shows the extent of our dissatisfaction.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The government said the strike would &ldquo;disrupt parents&rsquo; lives&rdquo; and &ldquo;hold back children&rsquo;s education&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">A number of Bristol schools have announced they will be closed today, including Hannah More Primary in Old Market, Headley Park Primary in Bishopsworth and Holymead Infant and Junior School in Brislington.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Blaise Primary and Nursery School will also close for the day, along with Brentry Primary School, Easton Primary School and Filton Avenue Infant School.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The rally by teachers will begin at College Green at 10am and head to The Bristol Hotel on the Harbourside.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.42554621632345','-2.5742063868163996',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-16 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:54:05',0),
	(183,NULL,NULL,2,'Review: The not-so-clever Volvo V40 D3 R-Design','review_the_notsoclever_volvo_v40_d3_rdesign','Intelligent cruise control system reacts to distance of vehicles in front, but bad weather and bends seemed to confuse it','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Laser radar. It sounds like something off a sci-fi thriller, but we&rsquo;re actually talking about technology fitted to Volvo cars, those traditionally staid and dull vehicles, favoured by the flat cap brigade.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Today&rsquo;s hip and trendy Volvos are anything but and are packed with sophisticated technology that keeps the brand at the forefront of car design and manufacture. Its laser radar systems are a key ingredient.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">I&rsquo;m testing the V40 D3 R-Design, a performance five-door hatchback and it&rsquo;s fitted with an intelligent yet simple to operate cruise control. As you might expect this keeps the car travelling at the desired speed but unlike most systems it also measures the distance of the car in front. This ensures that it keeps the Volvo at a safe distance behind.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">It does this by automatically braking and accelerating thanks to the information relayed by its laser radar. This distance can be changed from reasonably close to quite far away depending on driving conditions.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">In theory this is a valuable tool that should mean that the driver can relax. Not so though. My test takes place in torrential downpours and high winds and I discover that the radar is not infallible. This becomes particularly noticeable while at 70mph round a bend on a dual carriageway. The Volvo is in the outside lane but on approaching the bend there is a car on the inside and the radar picks this up and brakes abruptly despite there being no cars in front of me. This annoys me and I cancel the function.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">On another occasion we are on a straight road and high winds cause a flashing red warning bar on the driver&rsquo;s side of the dashboard to light up &ndash; accompanied by a really loud beep &ndash; for absolutely no reason whatsoever. My sleeping children wake up. High side winds seem to completely throw the radar and despite there being no traffic in front the Volvo brakes sharply from 70mph to 50mph.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">That said this cruise control is quite impressive when you bear in mind that it can be set at say 50mph and if a sharp incline appears the resulting gear change does not cancel out the cruise control. Often this is the case in many other vehicles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Another safety feature is the Blind Spot Information System. There&rsquo;s a little light on the inside of the wing mirror that glows red whenever a vehicle appears in the blind spot. This is useful because the design is prone to blind spots especially at the rear, making it a little awkward to reverse but there are helpful sensors fitted that bleep to alert the driver of nearby obstacles.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">As a driver&rsquo;s car the Volvo is engaging and the R-Design model, which comes with big alloys, a smooth power delivery for a diesel and a low chassis, corners really well. To give it a good run I drive it to Sandbanks, Poole, West Stafford near Dorchester and a lovely little village near Didcot, Oxford. All are places we had not visited before, so why not? With an average fuel consumption of over 65mpg it will easily cover over 600 miles on its 60 litre tank. It is fitted with engine start/stop.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">These relatively long journeys in generally heavy lashing rain allow me to experience the car in the worst conditions. At one point it rains so heavily that even with the wipers on the fastest speed it is impossible to see and thankfully traffic eventually slows to a crawl.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">I find the leather sports seats too hard and not supportive enough for my lower back and there is a disappointing lack of a footrest for the driver&rsquo;s left foot. I struggle with operating the heating because both left and right sides of the car are operated from a single dial near the driver &ndash; the switch that&rsquo;s incorporated has to be pushed once for left and again for right. It&rsquo;s all a bit confusing for a simple soul when they&rsquo;re focusing on the road so luckily my wife is there to operate the more technical things.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">In the back, eldest daughter Harriett quickly learns how to operate the electric windows (while sister Heidi dozes) but it is easy to lock them from the front. This time I remember to engage the child lock on her door.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The boot is large enough for our single pushchair.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">This 150bhp 2-litre diesel is a gutsy car that has enough power when required. Finished to a high standard the sound of the engine can be heard on tick over, which does alert the occupants to the fact that they&rsquo;re in a diesel.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.46705739396484','-2.609225307714837',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:18:13',0),
	(184,NULL,NULL,2,'Spike Island Director Helen Legg to help judge Turner Prize 2014','spike_island_director_helen_legg_to_help_judge_turner_prize_2014','Helen Legg, director of one of Bristolâ€™s most vibrant arts spaces reveals all about her experience and vision','<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div class=\"entry-content\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; clear: both; line-height: 21px; font-size: 14px; font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; color: #000000; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; background-color: #ffffff;\">\r\n<p>As Bristol&rsquo;s reputation for being a city where exciting work by new and established artists working in media including fine art, film and sound art and live art is incubated, encouraged, commissioned and exhibited we took the opportunity to talk to Helen Legg the Director of Spike Island.</p>\r\n<p>Spike Island is an international centre for the development of contemporary art and design. Home to studios, galleries, creative business workspaces and an excellent caf&eacute; Spike Island should be high up on anyone&rsquo;s list of galleries and art spaces in the UK to visit.</p>\r\n<p>Helen has been the director of Spike Island for several years now. Previously she was Curator at the renowned Ikon, Birmingham, where she worked for 5 years on exhibitions and offsite projects as well as the development of Ikon Eastside, a second gallery based in a former factory building in Digbeth, an industrial area of the city.</p>\r\n<p>In 2014 she is a judge for the Turner Prize and the CAS Annual Award, and in 2013 was a selector for the Paul Hamlyn Artist&rsquo;s Awards. She is chair of Visual Arts South West, an advisor for the Bristol Cultural Development Partnership and serves on the acquisition committee for Frac Midi-Pyr&eacute;n&eacute;es 2012-15.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">How long have you been the director of Spike Island and what attracted you to the role?</strong></p>\r\n<p>I became Director in September 2010, so nearly four years ago. At the time I had a job I loved and wasn&rsquo;t looking to leave particularly, but it felt right. It seemed a fascinating model for a visual arts organisation, with a loyal community of artists in-house, incredible gallery spaces and huge potential for development. It was a moment too in which many people were trying to figure out how you could sustain artists outside London and Spike felt like an answer to that. It&rsquo;s interesting to see how many new organisations in regional cities across the country are adopting the same model now.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Spike Island is home to some very highly regarded artists such as Louisa Fairclough and Richard Broomhall who have received high praise in the national press as well as specific art publications. How does Spike attract artists of such a high calibre?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Mostly artists hear us about through word of mouth; with Louisa, our former curator had seen an exhibition of hers and encouraged her to apply when she heard that she planned to move to Bristol. UWE&rsquo;s Fine Art BA course is also strong and as it&rsquo;s based in the building, we get a lot of applications from graduates. A good art school is a crucial ingredient for a great arts scene.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">What criteria are used re. studio space at Spike Island. Can anyone hire a studio there?</strong></p>\r\n<p>Essentially we&rsquo;re looking for promising artists at any stage of their career who we believe will make the most of the resources here. Anyone can apply and decisions are made by a panel including existing studio artists and myself. While we&rsquo;re clear about what we&rsquo;re looking for, it&rsquo;s never quite the same twice.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">How do you feel Spike Island supports its artists with studios in situ?</strong></p>\r\n<p>The exhibitions programme is important &ndash; the art world is global, so ideas change quickly and constantly. As an artist you have to find a way to be part of the larger conversation, or at least to have an awareness of it. Seeing plenty of new work, from Britain and overseas is essential. We also return 10% of studio rents to the artists themselves to enable them to self-organise activity and run a separate Associates programme that&rsquo;s focussed on developing artists and building their networks.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">As well as being home to numerous artists working in various media Spike Island also has a writer in residence, initially the Dundee International Book Prize nominee Amy Mason and currently Holly Corfield-Carr. Whose idea was it to have a writer in residence and how do you feel Spike Island assists them?</strong></p>\r\n<p>It was something I wanted to do. Writing and art making are so closely aligned; they&rsquo;re all about giving form to our experience and to me they&rsquo;re at their most exciting when they&rsquo;re struggling to articulate new experiences in the contemporary world. There was no existing support structure for young writers in Bristol either. We&rsquo;ve been able to give Holly and Amy time and space to work and to help them apply for funding. Amy wrote her novel Ida here, in a former ladies loo that for a while she turned into a museum of objects allegedly owned by her protagonist; we&rsquo;re thrilled that she&rsquo;s now up for the Dundee prize. Holly was recently commended by the Faber New Poets award; we were able to organise a residency in Ireland for her. We also launched a monthly book club, Novel Writers, with the Festival of Ideas, which introduces debut novelists. Bristol based writer Nathan Filer was our most recent guest, and he talked about his Costa book prize winning novel The Shock of the Fall, which is largely based in the city. Bristol has a wealth of talented young writers.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">What do you believe sets Spike Island apart from other artist spaces and galleries?</strong></p>\r\n<p>For artists, it&rsquo;s not just a gallery but a whole ecosystem. And for audiences, well, there are few places where you can see an exhibition, then end up sharing a table with the artist in the caf&eacute; or pop to their studio for a look at work in progress. It&rsquo;s a very special place.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">What events at Spike Island and beyond should Bristol 24-7 readers put in their diaries?</strong></p>\r\n<p>You should come to our next opening at 6pm on 11 July. We&rsquo;ve developed an exhibition with French artist Aurelien Froment that includes a collaboration with the wonderful Italian designer Martino Gamper. Openings are great ways to see exhibitions in a social environment, which is code for &lsquo;with a glass of wine in your hand&rsquo;. And the next Novel Writers takes place on 17 July with Lauren Owen, author of The Quick.</p>\r\n<p><strong style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Which artists alive or dead would you like to have studios at Spike Island?</strong></p>\r\n<p>All the lost, anonymous ones. I&rsquo;d love to hold a convention at which we could bring back the cave painters, the makers of Ancient Egyptian and Etruscan sculptures, of the chalk drawings in the British landscape, the women who embroidered the Bayeux Tapestry, the architect of the Pantheon. There are so many questions to ask them. And I&rsquo;d love for them to find out what&rsquo;s happened to art since and to see what they made of it all.</p>\r\n</div>','','BS4 3EN','51.449141604851725','-2.5889692652343683',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:16:44',0),
	(185,NULL,NULL,2,'Clap, whoop, just donâ€™t crowd surf at Bristol Proms','clap_whoop_just_dont_crowd_surf_at_bristol_proms','Artistic director of Bristol Old Vic wants audiences to forget classical etiquette, despite academic being thrown out of Handelâ€™s Messiah performanc','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The artistic director of the Bristol Old Vic has said he will continue to let classical music audiences &ldquo;clap and whoop&rdquo; during performances.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">But Tom Morris has been accused of hypocrisy by a Bristol University scientist who was thrown out of the Old Vic by fellow audience members after attempting to crowdsurf during a performance of Handel&rsquo;s Messiah.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Dr David Glowacki was so overcome during the &lsquo;Hallelujah Chorus&rsquo; he began lurching from side to side with his hands raised and whooping before attempting to crowd surf, witnesses claimed.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Audience members tried to physically eject the academic from the area, in what Mr Morris claims is the first such incident at a classical concert since the 18th century.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Mr Morris insisted it was &ldquo;a good thing&rdquo; as it showed people felt able to react to the music without inhibition.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">He promised to continue encouraging freedom of expression and behaviour throughout this year&rsquo;s Bristol Proms, which he launched as a more &ldquo;accessible and informal&rdquo; alternative to the traditional classical concerts.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Some ticket holders are now urging Mr Morris to set clearer guidelines for acceptable behaviour but the director is unwilling to re-impose the strict rules of etiquette which he has sought to cast off.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Dr Glowacki is an eccentric and a genius and only a very few people are likely to react to the music the way he did but it shows it is an environment in which unexpected things can happen,&rdquo;&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10914710/Classical-music-audiences-should-be-free-to-behave-how-they-wish-says-leading-director.html\" target=\"_blank\">Mr Morris told The Daily Telegraph at the weekend.</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;The only caveat I would add is that it really is about the music and maybe in some ways his reaction wasn&rsquo;t about the music but about testing how far he could push his behaviour based on the relaxed ethos.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;It brings attention to the fact we&rsquo;re presenting classical music in a different way and for the most part, it enables people to listen and hear the music better and get more excited by it.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Dr Glowacki accused both Morris and his fellow audience members &ndash; two of whom he described as &ldquo;classical vigilantes&rdquo; &ndash; of hypocrisy in only approving of the right sort of &ldquo;free&rdquo; behaviour.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Classical music, trying to seem cool and less stuffy, reeks of some sort of fossilised art form undergoing a midlife crisis,&rdquo; the expert in non-equilibrium molecular reaction dynamics, who is a visiting scientist at Stanford University, said.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.44871367913761','-2.5632200586913996',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 10:56:00',0),
	(186,NULL,NULL,2,'Review: The multi-purpose Peugeot 5008','review_the_multipurpose_peugeot_5008','The 5008 is more compact, making it more enjoyable to drive, but does mean that if there are seven passengers thereâ€™s not a huge amount of room for ','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Transporting seven people in comfort can present a problem unless of course you don&rsquo;t mind Transit vans. Peugeot has a solution though in its 5008 MPV (multi-purpose vehicle). Unlike the earlier Peugeot 807 people carrier the 5008 is more compact, making it more enjoyable to drive but this does mean that if there are seven passengers there&rsquo;s not a huge amount of room for luggage. Importantly for the driver it&rsquo;s not too difficult to reverse or manoeuvre.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">This style of vehicle is quite van like in terms of appearance but it is very much like a car to drive and driver appeal is one of the advantages of the Peugeot. The test model, a two-litre diesel Allure &ndash; top-of-the-range, is equipped with a six speed automatic gearbox but it can also be driven like a manual.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">At low speeds, typically up hill, this gearbox is a little indecisive not sure whether to go for third gear or second, which does make for the occasional uncomfortable jolt.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">It is quite frugal for a vehicle of its size, returning over 40mpg on average. I put it through its paces over a long weekend to Pembrokeshire where we experienced a variety of roads. On the motorway (the M4, over the Severn Bridge) it was very capable, happily cruising at 70mph, even though it is heavily laden with five passengers and luggage. Cruise control makes life so much easier on such travels and the electric child lock engaged by the click of a switch on the driver&rsquo;s door is easy to operate.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The one-way streets, invariably up sharp inclines in this part of the world, certainly cause the tired motorist some confusion but thank goodness I&rsquo;m driving the 5008 because the auto box makes light work of the hills. I&rsquo;m not usually a fan of electronic handbrakes but the one fitted to this vehicle is quick and simple to engage and disengage.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Inside, the Allure benefits from an enormous panoramic glass roof (with electric sliding cover), which makes the vehicle really light and airy. The front passengers get captain style seats with pull down armrests that can be adjusted to the desired height. The driver&rsquo;s seat is certainly comfortable, hardwearing and supportive although I do find that when my daughter&rsquo;s baby seat is in place behind I cannot push my seat back quite as far as I might desire.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">There are all the gadgets the modern day motorist could dream of including sat nav, a useful head-up display showing the speed and ensuring the driver doesn&rsquo;t take their eyes off the road. Air conditioning and a good quality sound system are all part of the package.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">I like the way that the centre of the dash, with all the controls for the air conditioning, slopes forward at an angle towards the windscreen, in quite a futuristic way. I also find the mirror above the rear view mirror useful for keeping an eye on our cheeky little daughters behind.</p>\r\n<h3 style=\"margin: 10px 0px; padding: 0px; font-size: 18px; line-height: 18px; font-family: arial, sans-serif; color: #cd1613;\">Fact file</h3>','','BS4 3EN','51.45967801020742','-2.553521190893548',NULL,NULL,0,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-16 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-08 09:41:51',0),
	(187,NULL,NULL,2,'Bristol streets to be haunted by shadowy ghosts of the past','bristol_streets_to_be_haunted_by_shadowy_ghosts_of_the_past','Bristolians will see their shadows replayed back to them on the cityâ€™s streets this September, thanks to the winners of the Playable City award','<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">Bristolians will see their shadows replayed back to them on the city&rsquo;s streets this September, thanks to the winners of the Playable City award.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">As the sun goes down and Bristol&rsquo;s street lights come on, traces of those who have passed by will be played back as shadows, re-animating the streets.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">As people interact with these curious figures, their movements and actions will be recorded and echoed back to the next visitor.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The aim of the project is to offer passers-by a trace of those who have walked the same path moments, days or weeks before, &ldquo;at times like ghostly time travellers, at others more like a more playful Peter Pan&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&lsquo;Shadowing&rsquo; is the brainchild of design duo Jonathan Chomko and Matthew Rosier, based in New York and Treviso, Italy, respectively.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">They will now work with the Watershed in Bristol to develop the infrared technology needed to capture people&rsquo;s outlines and work out ways to project movement back as shadows after people have moved on.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;We saw this as an opportunity to create a piece that lived in the city, rather than add on more infrastructure,&rdquo; said Jonathan Chomko.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">&ldquo;Our starting point was the notion that what makes our cities vibrant are the people we share them with, and we hoped to find a way to augment this presence. Our goal is to create unexpected interactions between people who share an urban environment by placing pockets of memory throughout the city that remember those who have passed through, allowing citizens to interact through time.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The Playable City Award is in its second year, and started in Bristol last year with the&nbsp;<a style=\"color: #cd1613; outline: none; text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;\" href=\"http://www.bristol247.com/2013/01/22/hello-lamp-post-whatcha-knowin-77166/\">Hello, Lamppost!</a>&nbsp;creation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The creators receive a &pound;30,000 cash prize to develop their idea. The award is co-funded by an expert network of organisations interested in exploring the future of creativity, technology and citizenship in urban spaces.</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-family: \'palatino linotype\', palatino, serif; font-size: 14px; line-height: 21px;\">The partners are: Future Cities Catapult, University of Bristol, University of the West of England and Bristol City Council. The Award is produced by Watershed with support from Arts Council England.</p>','','BS4 3EN','51.417036045801986','-2.572318111669915',NULL,NULL,1,0,0,0,NULL,NULL,'2014-07-04 00:00:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','2014-07-04 02:16:17',0),
